1. Nf3 {The QGD can arise via several different move orders. White can start
with 1.c4 or 1.Nf3 when the game may transpose to our repertoire.} (1. d4 Nf6
2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 ({After} 3. Nc3 {we can go for the Nimzo-Indian with} Bb4) 3...
d5 4. Nc3 Nbd7 {- This is our main move order.}) 1... d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4.
Nc3 Nbd7 {Our repertoire is based on this interesting move. However, there are
many alternatives.} (4... h6 {Some examples of typical ideas in the Carlsbad
structure:} 5. cxd5 (5. Bf4) 5... exd5 6. Bf4 c6 (6... Bd6) 7. e3 Bd6 8. Bg3
Bxg3 (8... O-O 9. Bd3 Bxg3 10. hxg3 Nbd7 11. Qc2 Re8 12. O-O Qe7 13. Rab1 Ne4
14. Rfe1 Ndf6 (14... Nd6 15. b4 Nf6 16. Ne5) 15. a3 Bf5 16. Rbc1 Nxc3 17. Bxf5
Nb5 18. Bd3 Nd6 19. b4 a6 20. a4 Rac8 21. Qb3 b5 22. axb5 axb5 23. Ra1 Nc4 24.
Ra6 Ne4) 9. hxg3 Bf5) (4... Be7) (4... c5) (4... c6) (4... dxc4) (4... Bb4) (
4... a6) 5. cxd5 {After this exchange, we get the Carlsbad structure.} exd5 6.
Bf4 {This and Bg5 are the most common moves. White should abstain from} (6. e3
c6 7. Bd3 Bd6 8. O-O O-O {when the bishop on c1 is shut in, and}) (6. g3 c6 7.
Bg2 Bd6 8. O-O O-O {with a misplaced bishop on g2. For example} 9. a3 Re8 10.
b4 a6 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gb6c4] and White's minority attack is ineffective.}) 6...
Nb6 {Black prepares ...Bf5 and a possible ...Nc8-d6. We will cover two
interesting alternatives in the theory session:} (6... c6 $5) (6... Bb4 $5) 7.
e3 (7. Nb5 {is well met by} Bb4+) 7... Bf5 8. Be2 Bd6 9. Bg3 O-O 10. O-O Ne4 ({
First giving White doubled pawns with} 10... Bxg3 $1 {would have been even
better.} 11. hxg3 Ne4) 11. Nxe4 Bxe4 {Black is doing great. In this structure
we do not exchange pieces to play for a draw, but to play for a win without
risk!} 12. Nd2 Bg6 (12... Bxg3 $5) 13. Bf3 (13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Rc1 c6 15. Nb3
Qe7 16. Nc5 Nc8 17. Re1 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gc8d6]} Nd6) 13... c6 14. Rc1 Re8 15.
Qb3 Bxg3 16. hxg3 {We may later exploit the hook on g3 with ...h5-h4. However,
first we improve the position of the b6-knight.} Qe7 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gb6c8,
Gc8d6]} 17. a4 (17. e4 $2 {just creates weaknesses.} dxe4 18. Rfe1 Qd6 {
Instead, Black can win with ...Qg5, but even if we examine the position
strictly from a positional point of view, Black has an advantage. For example}
(18... Qg5 $19) 19. Nxe4 Bxe4 20. Bxe4 Rad8 $15) (17. Rfe1 Rad8) 17... Nc8 18.
Qc3 Nd6 {Now, Black would like to exchange the light-squared bishops. Remember:
"The knight on d6 is a lonely piece!". It loses its value when there are too
many pieces on the board.} 19. b4 a6 20. Qc5 ({If} 20. Be2 {Black can start a
direct attack or prevent White's minority attack.} Rac8 {Black prevents b5 and
prepares to play ...b5 himself, creating a powerful outpost on c4.} (20... h5 {
also looks interesting, since I am not convinced that} 21. b5 {is good.} axb5
22. axb5 Nxb5 (22... cxb5) 23. Bxb5 cxb5 {It's very important that Black
controls b1. Even if White manages to win back the pawn, Black will have
counterchances with the passed b-pawn.}) 21. Qb3 b5 22. Ra1 Nc4 $17 {[%csl Gc4]
}) 20... Qd7 {Black should not exchange queens since this would reduce his
attacking potential.} 21. Rfe1 Rac8 22. Qb6 Bd3 23. Be2 $2 {A typical mistake
- the exchange of light-squared bishops plays into Black's hands.} Bxe2 24.
Rxe2 Re6 {Black has a strategically winning position. White will never be able
to carry out b5, while Black's attack on the kingside will be hard to meet.} ({
Or} 24... h5 25. Nf3 Qf5) 25. Nf3 $2 {A tactical blunder.} ({White should have
played} 25. Qc5 {when the game could have continued with} h5 {(using the hook
on g3 to open the h-file with an eventual ...h4)} 26. Qc2 Rce8 27. Nf3 (27. Nb3
Rh6 28. Nc5 Qg4 $17) 27... Nc4 $17) 25... Nc4 26. Qc5 b6 $19 {White's queen is
lost.} 27. Ne5 Rxe5 0-1

