1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 Nb6 7. e3 Bf5 8.
Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Be7 $2 (9... c6 {was better since now White could have played
Nb5.}) 10. O-O (10. Nb5 $1) 10... O-O 11. Rfc1 c6 {This move is necessary in
any case and should have been played earlier on.} 12. h3 Re8 (12... Nc4 13. b3
Nd6) 13. Rab1 a5 {Generally, I prefer this pawn to be on a6!} ({Let's look at
what happens, if both sides play exactly as in the game, but with the pawn on
a6 instead:} 13... a6 14. Qc2 Bd6 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. Na4 Nxa4 17. Qxa4 Ne4 18.
a3 Qe7 19. Qc2 g6 20. Nd2 Nd6 {Such positions occurred many times in practice,
and the verdict is clear: Black has better chances because White cannot carry
out a minority attack - the knight on d6 prevents b4-b5, while Black will
slowly but surely prepare actions on the kingside. White would rather have his
h-pawn on h2, not offering a target. We saw the structure with doubled pawns
on g2 and g3 in game one and already know that it is good for Black due to the
possibility of ...h5-h4.}) 14. Qc2 Bd6 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. Na4 $6 {Black is
happy to exchange some pieces, because the Nd6 "is a lonely piece". It does
not like crowded positions!} Nxa4 17. Qxa4 Ne4 18. a3 Qe7 19. Qc2 a4 $15 {
After fixing the queenside, Black has the idea of preparing ...b5 and ...Nc4.}
20. Nd2 Nd6 21. Qc5 Qd8 (21... h5 22. Nf3 g6 23. Ne5 Kg7 $15 (23... Ne4 $3 {
An exception to the rule: here it is good to trade queens!} 24. Qxe7 Rxe7 25.
Nf3 g5 $17 (25... h4 $3 $17 26. Nxh4 $140 Nd2 27. Ra1 Nb3 $19))) 22. Qb4 Qd7
23. Rc2 b5 $6 {This was not necessarry, although Black still keeps a small
advantage.} 24. Qc5 Nc4 {After having sealed off the queenside, Black will
concentrate his forces on the kingside.} 25. Nf3 f6 26. Re1 Re6 27. Ree2 Rae8
28. Ne1 Qd6 $2 {By exchanging queens, Black loses the greater part of his
advantage.} ({Black's attack would have been promising after} 28... g5 $1 29.
Nd3 Qg7 30. Qb4 f5 $17) 29. Qxd6 Rxd6 30. Nd3 Kf7 31. g3 g5 32. Kg2 Kg6 33. Rc1
Rde6 34. Rh1 Re4 35. Kf1 h6 36. Nc5 R4e7 37. Nd3 h5 38. h4 Re4 39. Nc5 R4e7 40.
Nd3 Re6 41. Nc5 R6e7 42. Nd3 Rf8 43. Nc5 Rfe8 44. Nd3 Rh8 45. Nc5 Kf5 46. Nd3
Kg6 47. Nc5 Rb8 48. Nd3 Ree8 49. Kg2 Re4 50. Nc5 Re7 51. Nd3 Rbe8 52. Kf1 Rb8
53. Kg2 Ree8 54. Kf1 Rbc8 55. Kg2 Re7 56. Kf1 Rg8 57. Kg2 Rh7 58. Rc2 Re7 59.
hxg5 fxg5 60. Ne5+ Nxe5 61. dxe5 Re6 62. f4 gxf4 63. gxf4 Kf5+ 64. Kf3 Rh6 65.
Rch2 Rgh8 66. Rh4 c5 67. Rd1 Ke6 68. Rg1 b4 69. axb4 cxb4 70. Rc1 Kd7 71. e4
dxe4+ 72. Kxe4 a3 73. bxa3 bxa3 74. Ra1 Ra8 75. Ra2 Rhh8 76. Rh3 Ra4+ 77. Kf5
Rf8+ 78. Kg6 Raxf4 79. Raxa3 Ke6 80. Ra6+ Kxe5 81. Rxh5+ Ke4 82. Ra4+ Kf3 83.
Rxf4+ Rxf4 84. Rf5 Rxf5 85. Kxf5 1/2-1/2

