1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 Nb6 7. e3 Bf5 ({
Another good example of how to play with Black:} 7... Bd6 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. Be2
Bg4 10. O-O O-O 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 c6 13. Rc1 Qe7 14. Be2 Nc8 15. Re1 Nd6 16.
Qc2 Rac8 17. a3 a6 18. Red1 Nfe4 19. Nxe4 Nxe4 20. Bf1 g6 21. Bd3 Nd6) 8. Bd3
Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Bd6 10. Bg5 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. Ne5 c6 13. h3 (13. f4 $2 Ne8 14.
Bxe7 Qxe7 $15) 13... Nfd7 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 {Black is already on the
better side of equality.} 16. Qc2 (16. f3 {with the idea of preparing e4, does
not bother Black. For example} Rad8 (16... f5 {is also possible but not
necessary.}) 17. Rad1 Rfe8 (17... Nc4 $1 $19 {wins material, but we are
looking at the position from a strategic view.}) 18. e4 dxe4 19. fxe4 Na4 20.
Rfe1 Nxc3 21. Qxc3 h6 $15 {White's central pawns are rather weak than strong,
though he can keep the balance.}) 16... Nc8 17. Na4 (17. e4 dxe4 18. Nxe4 Nb6
$15) 17... Nd6 {[%csl Gd6] Black's knight has reached its ideal position. In
the further course of this blitz game, Shulalova managed to develop a strong
attack on the kingside:} 18. Nc5 h5 19. b4 a6 20. a4 Qg5 21. Nd7 Rfe8 22. Ne5
Re6 23. Nf3 Qe7 24. Qc5 Re8 25. Rfe1 g5 26. Ne5 Rh6 27. Qc2 f6 28. Nd3 Qe6 29.
Nc5 Qc8 30. f3 g4 31. hxg4 hxg4 32. fxg4 Qxg4 33. Qf2 Rg6 34. Kf1 Re7 35. Qf3
Qh4 36. Qh3 Qg5 37. Kf2 Nc4 38. e4 Qd2+ 39. Kf1 Qf4+ 40. Kg1 dxe4 41. Nxb7 Reg7
42. Qc8+ Kh7 43. Ra2 Nd2 44. Qh3+ Rh6 45. Qe3 Nf3+ 46. Kf2 Qg3+ 47. Ke2 Qxe1#
0-1

