1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 Nb6 7. e3 Bf5 8.
Ne5 Bd6 9. Be2 c6 10. O-O O-O 11. a4 a5 {Here, this makes a lot of sense -
fixing the structure on the queenside makes it impossible for White to carry
out a minority attack.} 12. Qb3 Ne8 13. Bg3 Rb8 ({Let's clarify: the position
after} 13... Be6 14. Bd3 {would be much less favourable for Black than the one
in the game. Controlling the diagonal b1-h7 is very important!}) 14. Rfc1 Nd7
15. Qd1 Qe7 {Finally, Black succeeds in getting rid of the e5-knight. After}
16. Bd3 Bxd3 17. Nxd3 Bxg3 18. hxg3 Nd6 $15 {Black has an ideal position, with
good prospects on the kingside. Eventually, Black will use the hook created by
White's pawn on g3 to open the h-file with ...h5-h4.} 19. Rab1 Ra8 20. Qh5 Nf6
21. Qe2 h5 22. Ne5 g6 23. Qe1 Kg7 24. Ne2 Ng4 $1 $17 25. Nxg4 $2 hxg4 $19 {
The opening of the h-file proves disastrous for White.} 26. Rc5 Rh8 27. Rxa5
Rae8 {White has won a useless pawn on the queenside, whereas Black is about to
start her mating attack.} 28. Qb4 (28. Rc5 Rh6) 28... Rh6 29. Rc1 Qe4 $1 {
and White resigned because of} 30. Qxd6 Reh8 31. Kf1 Rh1+ 32. Ng1 Qd3+ 33. Ke1
Rxg1# 0-1

