1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nd7 4. Nc3 Ngf6 5. Bf4 Bb4 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Rc1 Ne4 8.
Nd2 Nxd2 9. Qxd2 Nf6 10. e3 Bf5 $1 {Black should use the opportunity to place
his bishop on f5.} ({If} 10... c6 {White plays} 11. Bd3 {, when after for
example} Bd6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. O-O O-O 14. f3 Be6 $14 {Black's position is
playable, but slightly worse.}) 11. Bd3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 c6 13. O-O O-O 14. a3 Be7
({Black avoids} 14... Bd6 15. Bxd6 (15. Bg5 Bxh2+) 15... Qxd6 {since he
prefers to put his knight on d6 instead of the queen.}) 15. Bg5 {Now, there
are two moves to consider:} a5 {, and} (15... Ne8 {with the idea of putting
the knight on d6.} 16. Bxe7 ({After} 16. Bf4 {Black can play} Bd6 {, hoping for
} (16... a5) 17. Bg3 Bxg3 18. hxg3 Nd6 {, when we already know how to exploit
the doubled pawns!}) 16... Qxe7 17. b4 ({After} 17. f3 {the move} f5 {is
possible.}) 17... a6 18. Rb1 Nd6 {Black has reached the optimal setup.}) 16.
Bxf6 {Ding uses his chances to exchange the knight before it can be
transferred to d6. The game is balanced after this.} Bxf6 17. Na4 Be7 18. Nc5
Qc7 19. Rc2 Bd6 20. g3 a4 21. Rc3 Ra5 22. Qc2 Rfa8 23. Kg2 g6 24. Re1 Qe7 25.
Rc1 Kg7 26. Qd1 h5 27. h4 R8a7 28. Qc2 Kh7 29. Qd1 Kg7 30. Nd3 Rb5 31. Qf3 Ra6
32. R1c2 Rab6 33. Kf1 Rb3 34. Rxb3 Rxb3 35. Nc1 Rb5 36. Ne2 Rb3 37. Nc1 Rb6 38.
Ne2 Rb3 39. Nc1 1/2-1/2

