{An amazing game from Black's perspective!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3
Bb4 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 h6 7. Bh4 O-O 8. e3 Bf5 $5 {The positionally desirable
move. This time, it is connected to concrete opening theory.} 9. Bd3 {After
this, Black is fine.} (9. Qb3 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Nbd7 $1 {This pawn sacrifice is
the justification of 8...Bf5.}) 9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 11. O-O c6 12. Ne5 {
Nxd7 is threatened - Black steps out of the pin with} Qe8 13. Bxf6 Nxf6 14. Qc2
Bd6 {The optimal setup for Black.} 15. Nd3 Qe7 {Preventing b4.} 16. g3 h5 17.
Rfe1 Rae8 ({I would have preferred} 17... Rfe8 {as in this case, Black would
retain the idea of playing} 18. Qe2 g6 19. Rab1 a5 20. a3 Qe6 21. b4 b5 $1 {
- here the rook is still very useful on the a-file!}) 18. Qe2 g6 19. Rab1 a5
20. a3 Qe6 21. b4 axb4 22. axb4 b5 {Black fixes the queenside to be able to
turn his full attention to the kingside. The weakness of the c6-pawn is not
much of a factor.} 23. Rbc1 h4 $17 {Black will continue with ...Kg7, ...Rh8,
etc. The c6-pawn can be easily defended.} 24. Nb1 Qd7 25. Nd2 Kg7 26. Nf3 hxg3
27. hxg3 Ng4 28. Nh2 (28. Kg2 Rh8 29. Rh1 Qf5 $17) 28... Nxh2 29. Kxh2 Rh8+ 30.
Kg1 g5 $19 {Black has several tempting attacking possibilities; his attack can
hardly be stopped.} 31. Qf3 g4 32. Qg2 Rh6 33. Kf1 Reh8 34. Ke2 Rh2 35. Qg1 Qf5
{Here, Black started to lose the thread a little, yet he still managed to win.}
(35... R8h3 $1 {[%cal Gd6g3]} 36. Kd1 Qf5 $19) 36. Kd2 Qf3 37. Kc3 Rg2 38. Qf1
Rhh2 39. Kb3 Rxf2 40. Nxf2 Rxf2 41. Qd3 Bxg3 42. Rxc6 Rb2+ 43. Kxb2 Bxe1 44.
Qxb5 g3 45. Rc8 Qf2+ 46. Kb1 Qf5+ 47. Rc2 g2 48. e4 Qxe4 0-1

