1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 Nbd7 6. e3 Bb4 7. cxd5 exd5 8.
Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. Qc2 h6 11. Bh4 Be7 {Black cannot do without this move.
Now White is up a tempo in a well-known theoretical line. However, Mamedjarov
demonstrated, his good knowledge of the typical ideas and soon equalised!} 12.
Rab1 Ne4 $1 13. Bxe4 Bxh4 14. Bh7+ Kh8 15. Bf5 g6 16. Bh3 Kg7 17. b4 Nb6 $1 18.
Bxc8 Rxc8 {Now Black is fine.} 19. Nd2 (19. b5 c5 $1 $11) 19... Be7 $1 {
The bishop is rerouted to d6.} 20. a4 Bd6 21. Qd3 a6 22. g3 Qe7 $15 {By now,
Black is doing great. He can improve his position on the kingside, whereas
White is stuck on the queenside.} 23. Na2 $2 {White blunders a pawn in this
blitz game.} (23. a5 $6 Nd7 24. Na2 Nf6 $15 {White has no more play on the
queenside.}) (23. b5 $2 cxb5 $1 24. axb5 a5 $1 {is very good for Black.} 25.
Ra1 Bb4 $17) 23... Nxa4 $19 24. Nb3 Nb6 25. Nc5 Nc4 26. Nc3 b6 27. Nxa6 Ra8 28.
b5 cxb5 29. Nb4 Bxb4 30. Nxd5 Ra3 31. Qc2 Qd6 32. Nxb4 Ra4 33. Qc3 h5 34. Nd3
Ra3 35. Qc2 Qd7 36. Ne5 Nxe5 37. dxe5 Rd3 38. Rfd1 Rxd1+ 39. Rxd1 Qe6 40. Rd6
Qxe5 41. Rxb6 Rb8 42. Rxb8 Qxb8 43. Qc3+ Kg8 44. Qb4 Qb7 45. h4 Qc6 46. Qe7
Qc1+ 47. Kg2 Qc6+ 48. e4 Qb6 49. Qe8+ Kg7 50. Qe5+ Kf8 51. Qh8+ Ke7 52. Qe5+
Kd7 53. Qd5+ Ke8 54. Qe5+ Kd8 55. Qd5+ Kc8 56. Qxf7 b4 57. Qb3 Kd7 58. e5 Ke7
59. Kf3 Qc6+ 60. Ke3 Qc5+ 61. Ke4 Qc6+ 62. Kd4 Qb6+ 63. Ke4 Qc5 64. f4 Qc6+ 65.
Kd4 Qb5 66. Ke4 Qc5 67. Qa4 Qc4+ 68. Ke3 Qc3+ 69. Ke4 b3 70. Qa7+ Kd8 71. Qb6+
