1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 Nbd7 8. Rc1
c5 $1 {The most solid line for Black. It often leads to symmetrical positions
with open c- and d-file.} 9. cxd5 Nxd5 $1 10. Bxe7 ({If} 10. Nxd5 {then} Bxh4)
10... Nxe7 $1 {Black avoids any weaknesses and will have no particular trouble
to develop his c8-bishop.} (10... Qxe7 $2 {would lead to a long-term advantage
for White} 11. Nxd5 exd5 12. dxc5 Nxc5 13. Be2 (13. Qxd5 $16)) 11. Bb5 (11.
dxc5 Nxc5 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Be2 b6 14. O-O Bb7 {Given a choice, I would prefer
Black's position - his b7-bishop is more active than White's counterpart on e2.
} 15. Rfd1 Nd5 (15... Kf8) 16. Nxd5 Bxd5) 11... cxd4 12. Qxd4 Nf6 13. O-O Qxd4
14. Nxd4 Rd8 15. Rfd1 Bd7 {Black has solved all opening problems. It's very
instructive to see how he outplays his opponent from this equal position.} 16.
Be2 Rac8 17. Bf3 b6 18. Bb7 Rb8 19. Ba6 Nc6 20. Kf1 Kf8 21. a3 Nxd4 22. Rxd4
Bc6 23. Rxd8+ Rxd8 24. f3 {Not a mistake according to the computer, but
letting Black's rook enter on the 2nd rank leads to some problems.} Rd2 25. b4
Ne8 26. Be2 Bb7 27. Ke1 Rb2 28. Nd1 Ra2 $15 29. Rc3 f5 {Gaining space and
preventing e4.} 30. h3 Ke7 31. g4 Kf6 32. b5 g5 33. Rd3 Ke7 34. Nc3 Ra1+ 35.
Kf2 Nf6 36. a4 Rc1 37. Bd1 Nd7 38. Ne2 Ra1 39. Ng3 $2 {Finally White cracks.} (
39. Nd4 $15) 39... Ra2+ 40. Kf1 Ne5 (40... f4 $1 41. exf4 gxf4 42. Nh5 (42. Ne2
Ne5 $19) 42... Nc5 43. Rc3 e5 $19) 41. Rc3 Kd8 42. Rc2 Ra1 43. Rd2+ Ke7 44. Kf2
Nc4 45. Rd4 Ra2+ 46. Ne2 Ne5 $17 47. f4 Nf3 48. Rc4 Bd5 49. Rc2 Ra1 50. Rc1
Rxc1 51. Nxc1 Nd2 52. Ne2 Ne4+ 53. Kg1 fxg4 54. hxg4 Kd6 55. Nd4 Kc5 56. f5 e5
57. Ne2 Kc4 58. Bc2 Nf6 59. e4 Bxe4 60. Bxe4 Nxe4 61. Kg2 Nf6 0-1

