1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 {4.Nc3 and 4.g3 (the Catalan) are the main moves
in this position, and we will deal with the first one in Lessons 3 to 7.  In
Lesson 2, we examine White's alternatives on move four except for 4.g3: I have
already published a repertoire against the Catalan on modern-chess.com.} 4. Bg5
$5 {This is a playable move. We can always continue with a classical Queen's
gambit move like 4...Nbd7!?, most likely transposing to our repertoire after 4.
Nc3 Nbd7 5.Bg5.} (4. cxd5 {This has been played by many great players. It is a
bit premature and they know it! However, the idea is to get out of book early
on and play a typical Carlsbad position!} exd5 5. Nc3 (5. Qc2 {White takes
control of the b1-h7 diagonal, 5.Qc2 is premature!} Nc6 $3 6. a3 (6. Bg5 $2 Nb4
$1 7. Qb3 Bf5 8. Na3 c6 $17 {Now it's impossible for White to get rid of the
powerful knight on b4!}) 6... Ne7 $1 7. Nc3 c6 8. Bg5 Bf5 9. Qb3 Qb6 10. Qxb6
axb6 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. e3 b5 $15 {[%cal Ge7c8,Gc8d6,Gc8b6,Gb6c4,Gd6c4,Gb5b4]
The pawn structure on the queenside is very good for Black, while his doubled
pawns on the f-file do not play a big role.}) 5... c6 $1 {Remember the rule:
Whenever Black plays ...c6 in the Carlsbad structure, he is quite often
threatening ...Bf5 since he is ready to meet Qb3 wth ...Qb6! From now on no
concrete theory is needed - its all about typical plans and ideas!} (5... Bf5
6. Qb3) 6. Qc2 $5 (6. Bg5 h6 $1 {This is the best move. It is useful to be
able to insert ...g7-g5 - see the line after 8.Qb3...} 7. Bh4 Bf5 $1 8. e3 (8.
Qb3 $6 g5 $1 {Here we see the point of playing ...h6!} 9. Qxb7 $2 (9. Bg3 Qb6
$15) 9... gxh4 10. Qxa8 Qb6 $1 $19 {and soon we will castle short and trap the
queen!}) 8... Nbd7 9. Bd3 (9. Be2 Be7 (9... Bd6 10. O-O O-O 11. Bg3 Bxg3 12.
hxg3 Ne8 13. Rc1 Nd6 14. Ne5 Re8 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. Bd3 Bxd3 17. Qxd3 h5)) 9...
Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Be7 $132 {Black is on the better side of equality - with all the
typical Carlsbad plans available!} (10... Bd6 $5 {This is also very good for
Black since e3-e4 will hardly ever be good for White!} 11. O-O (11. O-O-O $2 {
As always, this is just wrong!} Bb4 $3 12. a3 Bxc3 13. Qxc3 O-O 14. Ne5 Qc7 $15
(14... Qe8)) 11... O-O 12. Rab1 a5 $1 13. Qc2 Qe7 14. Rfe1 (14. a3 Rfe8 $15)
14... Qe6 $3 $36) 11. O-O O-O 12. h3 Re8 13. Rfe1 a5 $36) (6. Bf4 Bf5 $1 7. e3
(7. Nh4 Be6 $132 {White takes control of the important b1-h7 diagonal, but it
comes with the price of misplacing the knight!} 8. e3 Nbd7 9. Bd3 Bg4 $5 10.
Be2 (10. Nf3 Nh5 $36) (10. Qc2 Nh5 $36) 10... Bxe2 11. Qxe2 Ne4 12. Nf3 Ndf6
13. O-O Bd6 (13... Be7) 14. Bxd6 Nxd6 {Again, Black is at least equal.}) 7...
Be7 $5 $132 ({Or} 7... Bd6 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. Qb3 Nbd7 $1 (9... Qe7 $1 $11) 10.
Be2 (10. Qxb7 $6 Rb8 11. Qxa7 Rxb2 $36) 10... Rb8 11. O-O O-O 12. Rac1 Qe7 13.
h3 Ne4 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 $11) 8. Bd3 (8. Qb3 {is comfortably met with} Qb6) 8...
Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Nbd7 10. O-O O-O 11. h3 Re8 {Black has a good position; the line
can continue with} 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 Nd7 14. Bg3 Nb6 15. b3 Nc8 {[%cal
Gc8d6] with a good game.} (15... Bd6)) 6... g6 $1 {Black is fighting for the
important diagonal!} 7. Bg5 (7. Bf4 Bf5 8. Qc1 (8. Qb3 Qb6 $1 {If Qb3 can be
met with ...Qb6, this is almost always favourable for Black.} 9. h3 Qxb3 (9...
Ne4 $132) 10. axb3 Bb4 $132) 8... Nbd7 9. h3 Be7 $1 $132) 7... Be7 $1 {This is
important! Do not play 7...Bf5 right away!} (7... Bf5 $2 8. Qb3 $16) 8. e3 Bf5
9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 11. Bh6 {White can try to disturb Black in this way,
but it poses not a big problem.} (11. O-O O-O 12. h3 Re8 $132) 11... Bf8 {
This is a simple solution, though 11...Ng4 is also fine.} (11... Ng4 $5 12. Bf4
O-O 13. O-O Re8 14. h3 Ngf6 $132) 12. Bxf8 Kxf8 13. O-O Qe7 $1 {Taking e5
under control and preparing ...Ne4.} 14. h3 Kg7 15. Rab1 Ne4 $1 16. Qc2 Ndf6
$15 {This is just one sample line.}) (4. e3 {transposes to the Colle system.
White remains very flexible and he has several ways to develop his pieces. As
Black, we can for a universal setup: ...b6, ...Bb7, ...Bd6, ...0-0, ...Nbd7,
and - if needed - ...a6, with a solid position and some potential for
counterplay! In general, we do not play ...c5 but rather prepare ...Ne4 and
play on the kingside.} b6 $1 5. Nc3 (5. b3 Bb7 6. Bb2 Nbd7 7. Nbd2 {It also
makes sense to develop the knight to d2 instead of c3. It is less active there,
but it does not block the b2-bishop which helps White to control the e5 square.
Again, we do not really need to know the concrete theory. Every logical move
will do!} Bd6 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Ne4 $1 {This is the typical plan, though Black
also has other options:} (9... Qe7 $5) (9... c5 $5 10. cxd5 Nxd5 $1 11. Ne4 Be7
12. dxc5 Nxc5 13. Nxc5 Bxc5 $132) 10. Rc1 (10. Bxe4 $2 dxe4 11. Ne5 Bxe5 12.
dxe5 Qg5 $17) 10... a5 $5 $132 (10... Rc8 $5 $132) 11. Qc2 Ndf6) 5... Bb7 6. b3
(6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bb5+ c6 8. Bd3 Bd6 9. O-O O-O 10. b3 Nbd7 11. Bb2 Re8 $36)
6... Nbd7 7. Bb2 Bd6 8. Bd3 (8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O a6 10. Rc1 Qe7 (10... dxc4 11.
bxc4 c5 12. d5 exd5 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 $1 14. cxd5 b5 $36 (14... Re8 $4 15. a4 $16))
11. cxd5 exd5 $132) (8. cxd5 exd5 9. g3 (9. Be2 a6 10. O-O O-O $132 {Black has
nice play in this typical position. JUST REMEMBER: We usually don't play ...c5
here!}) (9. Rc1 a6 10. g3 O-O ({Black can also keep the option to castle
queenside:} 10... Qe7 {, and if} 11. Bg2 {then} O-O-O $3 $17) 11. Bg2 Re8 12.
O-O Ne4 (12... Qe7) 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Nd2 b5 $5 {A good positional move,
stopping Nc4.} 15. Qc2 Qe7 16. Rfe1 Bd5 $17 {All of White's minor pieces are
restricted!}) 9... a6 (9... O-O $5 $132) 10. Bg2 Qe7 11. O-O $2 O-O-O $3 {
This is very strong! Our king is safe enough on the queenside, while we start
an attack on the kingside.} 12. a4 Ne4 $15 {For example} 13. a5 Nxc3 14. Bxc3
b5 {Black is about to play ...h5-h4 while White has no more pawn breaks on the
queenside.}) 8... O-O 9. O-O a6 10. Rc1 dxc4 11. bxc4 c5 12. d5 exd5 13. Nxd5
Bxd5 $1 14. cxd5 b5 $132) (4. Qc2 {is yet another playable move, but it
promises nothing special.} dxc4 $1 5. e3 (5. e4 $6 b5 6. a4 c6 7. Nc3 Bb7 $15)
(5. Qxc4 $6 Nbd7 6. Bf4 (6. Qc2 c5 7. e3 b6 $15 {[%csl Gb7,Rc1][%cal Gc8b7]})
6... c5 7. e3 a6 $15 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7]}) 5... c5 6. Bxc4 (6. Qxc4 $2 Nbd7 $15
) 6... cxd4 (6... Nbd7 7. O-O a6 8. a4 cxd4 9. exd4 Be7 10. Nc3 Nb6 $132) 7.
Nxd4 (7. exd4 Nc6 $132) 7... Bd7 8. O-O Nc6 $11) 4... dxc4 $1 {This is
"officially" the best move. Now, White has to be careful not to end up worse!
Black is ready to defend c4 with ...b5. The only way to make sure to win back
the pawn is 5.Qa4+, in which case White loses some time by moving his queen.} (
{As already mentioned, the "lazy"} 4... Nbd7 $5 {is a good alternative.} 5. e3
h6 6. Bh4 Be7 7. Nc3 {and we transpose to the lines after 4.Nc3.} (7. Nbd2 {
This is nothing special, but it's different!} c5 (7... O-O 8. Bd3 (8. cxd5 exd5
) 8... c5 $132) 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 $132)) 5. e4 (5. e3 $2 {After this,
Black can defend his extra pawn.} b5 6. a4 c6 7. Nc3 Bb4 8. Be2 Nbd7 9. O-O Qb6
$15 {White has some practical compensation for the pawn, but it isn't quite
enough.}) (5. Qa4+ $6 Nbd7 $1 {Our general plan after this check is to go for .
..a6-b5-c5, then ...Be7, and castle. The move order depends on White's play.} (
5... Bd7 $6 6. Qxc4) 6. e3 (6. Qxc4 $2 {White has lost too much time with his
queen and he is going to lose some more after ...b7-b5 move! Black is at least
slightly better!} c5 7. e3 a6 $1 8. Qc2 (8. Bxf6 Qxf6 $15) (8. a4 {This fails
to prevent ...b5. Black has a great position after} cxd4 9. exd4 (9. Nxd4 $4
Qa5+ 10. Nc3 Qxg5 $19) 9... h6 10. Bh4 b5 $1 11. Qc2 Bb7 $17) 8... cxd4 ({or} 
8... b5 $15) 9. exd4 (9. Nxd4 $4 Qa5+ 10. Nc3 Qxg5 $19) 9... h6 10. Bh4 b5 $17
{Black has a very good version of an IQP position.}) (6. e4 {can be met with}
Be7 $1 {, unpinning the knight and threatening ...Nxe4.} 7. Nc3 (7. e5 $6 Nd5
8. Bxe7 Qxe7 9. Bxc4 O-O $15 (9... Qb4+ $5 $15)) 7... b5 $1 {This powerful
move is suggested by the computer!} (7... O-O $1 {is a simple and good
alternative.} 8. Qxc4 h6 9. Bh4 a6 $1 $36 10. e5 (10. Qb3 b5 11. Bd3 c5 $17)
10... Nd5 11. Bxe7 Nxe7 $15 {Black has good development - ...b5, ...Bb7 will
follow.}) 8. Qxb5 Rb8 9. Qxc4 Rxb2 {Now, White has to be very careful!} 10. Be2
(10. Na4 Nb6 $1 11. Nxb6 Rxb6 $3 12. Bd3 Ba6 13. Qa4+ Qd7 14. Qxd7+ Nxd7 15.
Bxa6 Bxg5 $15) 10... c5 11. O-O (11. dxc5 Nxc5 $17) 11... Rb4 12. Qd3 cxd4 $15)
(6. Nc3 {is met with the same typical ideas ...a6-b5-c5 (and maybe ...h6)!} a6
7. e4 Rb8 $1 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qe2 h6 10. Bh4 Be7 $36) 6... Be7 $1 7. Bxc4 (7. Qxc4
a6 8. Nbd2 c5 $36) 7... h6 $1 8. Bh4 a6 $1 9. Be2 (9. Qc2 b5 10. Be2 c5 11. O-O
Bb7 $15) 9... O-O 10. O-O c5 $15 (10... b5 11. Qc2 c5 12. dxc5 Nxc5 13. Bxf6
gxf6 $15)) (5. Nc3 a6 $1 6. a4 (6. e4 b5) 6... Nc6 7. e4 (7. e3 Na5 8. Nd2 (8.
Ne5 Bb4 9. Nxc4 Qd5 $1 10. Bxf6 (10. Nxa5 Ne4 $3 $17) 10... Nxc4 $1 11. Qb3
Nxe3 12. Qxb4 Nc2+ 13. Kd2 Nxb4 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bxg7 Rg8 16. Bh6 Bd7 $17 (
16... b6 $17)) 8... h6 9. Bh4 c5 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Nxc4 Qxd1+ 12. Rxd1 Nxc4 13.
Bxc4 Bd7 14. Ke2 Rc8 $15) 7... Na5 $1 8. e5 h6 9. Bh4 g5 10. Nxg5 hxg5 11. Bxg5
Be7 12. exf6 Bxf6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 $15) ({If} 5. Nbd2 {we can again defend the
pawn with} b5 (5... c5 {is also not bad.}) 6. a4 c6 7. e4 Be7 $17) 5... c5 $1
6. Bxc4 $5 {This is maybe the most interesting position that White can get. He
is hoping for reasonable practical compensation!} (6. e5 $2 h6 7. Bh4 g5 8. Bg3
Nh5 $15) (6. Nc3 cxd4 7. Qxd4 {White should take with the queen since} (7. Nxd4
$6 Bc5 $15 {is already good for Black.}) 7... Qxd4 8. Nxd4 a6 9. Bxc4 h6 $1 10.
Bd2 (10. Bxf6 $2 gxf6 11. Rc1 Bd7 $15) (10. Be3 $2 Ng4 11. Bd2 Bc5 12. Be2 h5
$17 13. Bxg4 hxg4 14. Be3 Nd7) (10. Bh4 Bd7 11. f3 Nc6 $132) 10... Bc5 11. Nb3
Ba7 12. O-O Nc6 $132) 6... cxd4 7. O-O (7. e5 $6 h6 8. Bc1 $5 (8. Bh4 $2 g5 9.
Bg3 (9. Nxg5 $4 hxg5 10. Bxg5 Qa5+ 11. Nd2 Qxe5+) 9... Nh5 $15) 8... Nfd7 $1 9.
O-O Nc6 10. Bf4 Be7 11. Re1 Nb6 12. Bb5 Bd7 13. Bxc6 bxc6 $3 14. Qxd4 c5 $15)
7... Nc6 8. Nbd2 (8. e5 $2 h6 9. Bh4 (9. Bc1 $5 Nd7 $1 10. Re1 (10. Bb5 Qb6 11.
Bxc6 bxc6 $17) 10... a6 $1 $15) 9... g5 10. Bg3 Ne4 $17 {is insufficient for
White.}) 8... h6 {This is best from a practical viewpoint!} (8... Bd6 {This is
also possible, but White gets annoying attacking chances:} 9. Bb5 $5 e5 10. Nc4
Qc7 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Rc1 O-O 13. Qd2 Be7 14. Qh6 Qd8 $1 {This is important!
Now} 15. Nh4 $2 {can be met with} f5 $1 16. Nxf5 Bxf5 17. exf5 Bg5 $19) 9. Bh4
(9. Bf4 Nh5 $5 (9... a6 $5) 10. Be5 a6 $1 11. Rc1 Be7 12. h3 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Nf6
$15) 9... Be7 10. e5 Nd5 11. Bxe7 (11. Bg3 O-O $11) 11... Ndxe7 12. Rc1 O-O 13.
Qe2 (13. Re1 b6 14. Bd3 Bb7 15. a3 Ng6 $1 $15) 13... Ng6 $132 *

