1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Bg5 dxc4 5. e4 Be7 (5... c5 $1 {is our move.})
6. Nc3 c5 7. Bxc4 cxd4 8. Qxd4 Qxd4 9. Nxd4 a6 {This position is quite similar
to our main line with 5...c5.} 10. a4 $6 {Creating weaknesses - ...b5 was not
a threat.} Nbd7 (10... Bd7 {, intending 11...Nc6, was a good alternative.}) 11.
Ke2 h6 12. Bd2 (12. Bh4 $2 {loses a pawn due to} Nxe4 $1 (12... g5 13. Bg3 Nh5
{would be a useful positional idea if 12...Nxe4 didn't exist.}) 13. Nxe4 (13.
Bxe7 Nxc3+ 14. bxc3 Kxe7 $19) 13... Bxh4 $19) 12... Ne5 13. Bb3 Bc5 14. Nc2 g5
$1 {I like this move, which secures the powerful e5-knight.} 15. h4 Rg8 {
Keeping the knight on e5 is more important than giving up control of the
h-file.} 16. hxg5 hxg5 17. Be3 b6 $1 $15 {Another strong positional move!
Since taking on c5 is beneficial for Black (due to the opening of the b-file),
he can keep the tension. Black is slightly better and managed to outplay his
opponent.} 18. f3 Bb7 19. Rad1 Ke7 20. Bd4 Bxd4 21. Nxd4 Rh8 22. Ke3 Ng6 23.
Nce2 Rad8 24. Rc1 Rxh1 25. Rxh1 Nf4 26. Rh2 Bxe4 27. g3 Nxe2 28. Rxe2 0-1

