1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. Bf4 $1 {This is a common and good
move! Black has several ways to play - our choice is a nice and very trendy
line, which offers good counterplay and chances to size the initiative!} (5. c5
$2 {This is a typical idea, but it does not work here.} b6 $1 $15 6. c6 {
This is the critical move - if White could defend c6 in time he would be doing
great.} (6. cxb6 axb6 7. Bf4 Ba6 $15) (6. b4 $2 {After this, Black destroys
White's pawn chain with the help of a piece sacrifice.} a5 7. c6 axb4 $3 8.
cxd7+ Bxd7 9. Nb1 c5 $17 {Black's mighty queenside pawns offer more than
enough compensation for the piece.}) 6... Nb8 7. Ne5 (7. Qa4 Ne4 $36 8. Bf4 Bd6
9. Bxd6 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Qxd6 11. Ne5 (11. e3 Nxc6 12. Bb5 Bd7 $17) 11... f6 12.
Nd3 Qxc6 $17) 7... Ne4 $1 $15 {This is the key move - Black prepares to drive
away the e5-knight with ...f6.} 8. Nxe4 (8. e3 Bb4) 8... dxe4 9. e3 Bb4+ 10.
Bd2 Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 f6 {Since White's queen is no longer on the d1-h5 diagonal,
this move is possible.} 12. Nc4 Nxc6 $17) (5. g3 $5 {This is a playable move!
White transposes to some kind of Calatan. However, we have a good way to meet
this:} dxc4 $1 6. Bg2 Rb8 $1 7. Qa4 (7. a4 a6 8. O-O Be7 9. Nd2 b5 10. axb5
axb5 11. Bc6 b4 12. Na4 Bb7 $1 13. Bxb7 Rxb7 14. Nxc4 Ra7 $3 15. b3 (15. Be3
Nd5 $11) 15... O-O $132) (7. e4 $2 b5 8. e5 Nd5 $17) (7. O-O $6 b5 8. Ne5 (8.
a4 $2 b4 9. Nb1 Bb7 10. Nbd2 c3 $17) 8... Nxe5 9. dxe5 Nd7 10. Be3 c5 $132 11.
a4 b4 12. Nb5 Qb6 $15) 7... a6 8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qd3 Bb7 10. O-O c5 11. Bf4 Rc8 $1
$36 {Black has a great game - White has lost too much time moving his queen!} (
11... c4 $5 12. Qc2 Rc8 $132)) (5. Qc2 $5 {Yet another interesting line! Black
has several alternatives to choose from:} Bb4 $5 {transposing into some sort
of Nimzo with Qc2} 6. a3 (6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bg5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 Ne4 {
transposes to the lines examined under the move order 5.cxd5 exd5 6.Bg5.} 10.
Nd2 (10. e3 h5 11. Bd3 h4 12. Bxe4 dxe4 13. Qxe4+ Kf8 14. Be5 f6 15. Nxg5 Nxe5
16. dxe5 Bxc3+ 17. bxc3 fxg5 $13) 10... Nxg3 11. hxg3 Nb6 $132 (11... c6 $132))
(6. Bg5 $6 dxc4 7. e4 (7. e3 $2 b5 8. a4 c6 $17) 7... c5 $3 $36 8. dxc5 (8. e5
$2 cxd4 9. exf6 gxf6 $17) 8... Qa5 $36) 6... Bxc3+ 7. Qxc3 O-O $1 {Black has a
good Nimzo-Indian because of the misplaced Qc3.} 8. Bg5 (8. cxd5 $6 exd5 9. Bg5
(9. Bf4 c5 $1 $36) 9... h6 10. Bh4 (10. Bxf6 $6 Nxf6 11. e3 Bf5 12. Bd3 Bxd3
13. Qxd3 Ne4 14. O-O Qe7 15. Nd2 Nd6 $1 $15) 10... c5 $1 11. e3 g5 12. Bg3 Ne4
13. Qc2 Qa5+ $1 14. Nd2 c4 $36) 8... h6 9. Bh4 (9. Bxf6 $6 Nxf6 10. e3 b6 $1
11. cxd5 (11. Be2 Bb7 12. O-O Ne4 13. Qc2 dxc4 14. Bxc4 c5 $15) 11... Nxd5 $1
12. Qc2 Bb7 13. Be2 c5 14. dxc5 Rc8 $15) 9... b6 $1 10. cxd5 (10. e3 c5 11. Be2
Ba6 $36) 10... exd5 11. e3 c5 $1 12. Bd3 (12. Bb5 g5 13. Bg3 Ne4 14. Qc2 Ndf6
15. O-O Bf5 $132) 12... a5 $1 13. O-O Ba6 $132) (5. e3 {This is very similar
to 4.e3 (compare Lesson 2).} a6 $1 {THIS is the best move order! Now White
needs to find 6.b3!} (5... b6 $6 {this is careless!} 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bb5 Bb7 8.
Ne5) 6. b3 $1 (6. cxd5 $6 exd5 $36) (6. Be2 $6 dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 8. Bd3 c5 9. O-O
Bb7 $17) (6. c5 $2 {Like on move 5, this is a mistake!} b6 $1 7. b4 $2 (7. c6
$2 Nb8 8. Ne5 Qd6 9. Qa4 Ne4 10. Nxe4 dxe4) (7. cxb6 cxb6 8. Be2 b5 $1 9. O-O
Bd6 10. b3 Bb7 $15) 7... a5 $1 8. c6 axb4 $3 $17 (8... Nb8 $4 9. b5) 9. cxd7+
Bxd7 10. Nb1 (10. Nb5 c6) (10. Ne2 c5 $17) 10... c5 $17) (6. Bd3 $6 dxc4 7.
Bxc4 b5 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. O-O c5) (6. Qc2 dxc4 7. a4 (7. Bxc4 b5 8. Bd3 c5 $36)
7... c5 (7... Bb4 8. Bxc4 b6 9. O-O Bb7 $132) 8. Bxc4 Qc7 9. Be2 b6 10. O-O Bb7
$15) 6... b6 7. Bd3 (7. Bb2 Bb7 8. cxd5 exd5 9. g3 Bd6 10. Bg2 Qe7 11. O-O
O-O-O $1 $15) (7. Bb2 Bb7 8. Be2 Bd6 9. O-O O-O 10. Rc1 dxc4 $1 (10... Qe7) 11.
bxc4 (11. Bxc4 $2 b5 12. Be2 c5) 11... c5 12. d5 (12. Nd2 Qc7 13. h3 Rfd8 $15)
12... exd5 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 $3 {REMEMBER TO TAKE WITH THE BISHOP IN SUCH
SITUATIONS!} 14. cxd5 b5 $1 $132 (14... Re8 $2 15. a4)) 7... Bb7 8. O-O Bd6 9.
Bb2 O-O 10. Qe2 dxc4 11. bxc4 (11. Bxc4 b5 12. Bd3 c5 13. dxc5 Nxc5 $17) 11...
c5 12. Rfd1 (12. d5 exd5 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 $1 14. cxd5 b5 (14... Nxd5 15. Bxh7+)
15. e4 Re8) 12... cxd4 13. exd4 Qc7 14. h3 Rfe8 $15 15. Rac1 Bf4 16. Rc2 h6)
5... Bb4 6. cxd5 {the only ambitious move!} (6. e3 $6 c5 {After this, Black
gets very good play with natural moves - no further theory is needed!}) (6. Qc2
$2 {This is just bad - we take the pawn!} dxc4 7. e4 (7. Nd2 c5 8. dxc5 Nxc5 9.
Nxc4 O-O $17) 7... b5 $17) (6. Qa4 $6 Bxc3+ $1 {This leads to nice, unclear
play!} (6... c5 $1 {is a good alternative.} 7. dxc5 (7. cxd5 $6 Nxd5 $36) 7...
Qa5 $1 8. Qxa5 Bxa5 9. Bd2 dxc4 10. e3 Nxc5 11. Bxc4 Bd7 $132) 7. bxc3 O-O 8.
e3 c5 $1 $132 (8... Nb6 $5 9. Qb3 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Nxc4 11. Qxc4 b6 $3 12. Bxc7 (
12. Qxc7 $2 Qxc7 13. Bxc7 Ba6 $3 $15 14. Rc1 Rfc8 15. Bd6 Nd5 $1 16. Kd2 Nf6 $3
17. Ke1 {Black is not going to repeat moves - after White can no longer castle,
we increase the pressure.} Rc4 $15) 12... Qd5 13. Qxd5 Nxd5 14. Bd6 Rd8 15. c4
Rxd6 16. cxd5 Rxd5 $132)) (6. Qb3 $6 c5 $1 7. e3 (7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3 O-O 9. e3
b6 10. Be2 Ba6 $15) (7. dxc5 Qa5 8. a3 Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 10. bxc3 Nxc5 11. e3
Bd7 $15) 7... Qa5 $36) 6... Nxd5 $5 {This is the new fashion! 7...exd5 is a
good alternative.} 7. Bd2 $1 {the only sensible move .} N5f6 $1 {This is the
starting position of the whole system. Black has a sound position, but we need
to know a few key details. For example, when it is the right moment to play ...
b6, or when to play ...0-0!} 8. Qc2 $1 {This is the most critical move!} (8. g4
$6 b6 $1 {The most accurate! Let's delay castling for a while!} 9. g5 Bxc3 10.
Bxc3 Ne4 11. Rc1 Bb7 12. h4 Bd5 $5 $36 {Black is at least equal!}) (8. a3 $5 {
With this, White wants to clarify the situation.} Bxc3 9. Bxc3 (9. bxc3 $6 b6
$5 (9... Ne4 $5 {is also quite good:} 10. Bf4 (10. Qc2 Nxd2 11. Qxd2 b6 12. e4
Bb7 13. Bd3 O-O 14. O-O c5 $11) 10... b6 11. Qc2 Bb7 12. e3 g5 13. Bg3 h5 14.
Bd3 f5 $36) 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bh4 Bb7 12. e3 Qe7 $132 13. Bd3 g5 $1 14. Bg3 h5 $36
) 9... b6 $1 {REMEBER! Quite frequently, we want to go for a fast ...b6!-Bb7,
rather than castling! In this way, we prevent e2-e4 after Qc2!} (9... O-O $6
10. Qc2 b6 11. e4 $132) 10. e3 (10. g3 {Black has absolutely no problems here:
we have good control of the light squares - a typical idea would be ...a7-a5!,
followed by putting our queen on b7!} Bb7 11. Bg2 O-O 12. O-O a5 $1 13. b4 (13.
b3 h6 14. Qc2 Qb8 $5 15. Qb2 Bd5 16. Rac1 Qb7 $36 (16... b5) 17. Rfd1 b5 $15) (
13. Rc1 Qb8 14. Re1 Rd8 $1 (14... Be4 $2 15. Ne5 $36) 15. e3 Bd5 16. Qe2 $2 Qb7
$15) 13... axb4 14. axb4 Qc8 (14... Bd5) 15. Qb3 Bd5 16. Qb2 Qb7 $15) 10... Bb7
11. Bd3 (11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O Ne4 13. Be1 (13. Rc1 c5 $132) 13... c5 $132) 11...
O-O 12. O-O (12. Qc2 $6 c5 $1 $36 13. Rd1 (13. dxc5 $2 Nxc5 $17 14. Bxf6 $4
Nxd3+ 15. Ke2 Qxf6) 13... Qc7 $36) 12... c5 $1 {We don't mind opening up the
position despite White having the pair of bishops because we have very active
pieces. White's bishops may come under attack!} 13. dxc5 (13. Qe2 Nd5 $1 14.
Bd2 cxd4 $1 15. Nxd4 Nc5 16. Bc4 Ne4 $132 (16... Nf4 $5)) (13. Rc1 Rc8 $132 (
13... Ne4 $5 $132) 14. Qe2 Ne4 15. Bxe4 Bxe4 16. Rfd1 Qe7 17. dxc5 Nxc5 $132)
13... Nxc5 14. Bc2 Qe7 $132 (14... Rc8 $132)) (8. e3 $6 {This natural looking
move does not appear to be good! If White is not precise, Black may take over!}
O-O $3 {After 8.e3, we DO play ...0-0 instead of b6. White has made clear that
he is not going for e2-e4. So we castle fast, and strike in the center with
either ...Be7!, followed by ...c5!, or ...Bd6! and ...e5!} 9. a3 (9. Bd3 b6 10.
O-O Bb7 11. a3 Be7 (11... Bd6 $132 12. e4 c5) 12. e4 $2 (12. Rc1 c5 $132) 12...
Nc5 $15) 9... Be7 $1 (9... Bd6 $5 10. e4 e5 11. d5 a6) 10. Bd3 (10. e4 $6 c5 $1
11. Qc2 (11. e5 $2 cxd4 12. Nb5 Ng4 $17) 11... cxd4 12. Nxd4 Nc5 13. Nf3 e5 14.
Nxe5 Be6 $15) (10. Be2 c5 11. O-O b6 12. Rc1 Bb7 $132 13. dxc5 (13. Ne5 $6 Nxe5
14. dxe5 Ne4 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 $15) 13... Nxc5 $15) 10... c5 11. O-O a6 $1 $132 (
11... b6 12. Qe2 Bb7 13. Rfd1 Qb8 $11) 12. a4 b6 13. Qe2 Bb7 14. Rfd1 Qb8 $1
$11) (8. g3 $1 b6 $1 {Black is in time to oppose the Catalan bishop on g2.} 9.
Qa4 $5 {This is an interesting suggestion by the computer. But it's not a big
deal:} (9. Bg2 Bb7 10. O-O O-O 11. Rc1 c5 $5 (11... a6 $1 {Another good option,
controlling b5.} 12. Qc2 (12. a3 Bd6 13. Qc2 c5 $132) (12. Qb3 c5 13. a3 Bxc3
14. Bxc3 Rc8 $132) 12... c5 13. a3 Rc8 $1 $132 (13... Bxc3 14. Bxc3 Be4 15. Qd2
Rc8 $132)) 12. a3 (12. Nb5 Bxd2 13. Qxd2 Qb8 $132 (13... Qe7 $5)) 12... Bxc3
13. Bxc3 (13. bxc3 $6 h6 $1 (13... Qe7 $15 14. a4 Rfc8 $15) (13... c4 $5) 14.
Bf4 Re8 $15) 13... Rc8 14. dxc5 Nxc5 $132) 9... Bxc3 10. Bxc3 Bb7 11. Bg2 O-O
12. O-O a5 $1 {White may be very slightly better, but black is solid and he
will get counterplay with ...c7-c5.} (12... Qe7 $5 13. Rac1 a5 14. Rfd1 Rfc8
$132) 13. Rac1 Qb8 14. Rfd1 Bd5 (14... Rc8 15. Bd2 c5 16. Bf4 Qa7) 15. Ne1 Qb7
$132) (8. Rc1 O-O (8... b6 $2 9. Nb5) 9. e3 {This is very similar to 8.e3. For
example} b6 $1 {Better than the immediate ...c5.} (9... c5 10. dxc5 Nxc5 11. a3
Bxc3 12. Bxc3 b6 $14) 10. Be2 (10. a3 Be7 11. Be2 (11. b4 $6 c5 (11... Bb7) 12.
dxc5 bxc5 13. b5 Bb7 $15 {White has the better pawn structure, but this is
more than compensated by Black's piece activity.}) 11... c5 {Black can also
play ...Bb7 first.} 12. O-O Bb7 13. Ne5 $6 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Ne4 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 $15)
10... Bb7 11. O-O (11. a3 Be7) 11... c5 12. a3 Bxc3 13. Bxc3 Nd5 14. dxc5 (14.
Bd2) 14... Nxc3 15. Rxc3 Nxc5 $11) 8... b6 $1 ({We need to avoid} 8... O-O $2
9. e4 h6 10. e5 Nd5 11. a3 $16) 9. e4 Bb7 10. Bd3 $5 (10. e5 Nd5 11. a3 $2 (11.
Bd3 c5 $132 {Black is doing good; for example} 12. O-O (12. Ne4 $2 cxd4 $17 13.
O-O O-O 14. Neg5 (14. Rfe1 Rc8 $17) 14... g6 $17) 12... Bxc3 $1 13. bxc3 cxd4
14. cxd4 h6 $1 $132) 11... Bxc3 $3 12. bxc3 (12. Bxc3 $2 c5 $17 (12... Rc8 $17)
) 12... Ne7 $1 13. Be2 c5 14. O-O h6 $15) 10... c5 $3 {A strong move - now
White must continue to play precisely since the initiative may easily pass to
Black!} 11. Nb5 $5 (11. O-O Bxc3 $3 12. Bxc3 (12. bxc3 $2 c4 $1 ({After} 12...
Rc8 $2 {White can consolidate with} 13. Qb1 c4 14. Bc2 $16 {[%csl Gc2,Gd2,Gd4,
Ge4]}) 13. Bxc4 Nxe4 $15) 12... c4 $3 13. Bxc4 Bxe4 14. Qe2 O-O 15. Ne5 (15.
Rfe1 Bb7 $132 (15... Bd5 $132) 16. Ne5 Nd5 17. Bd2 Nxe5 18. dxe5 Qh4 $36) 15...
Bb7 16. Rad1 Nd5 17. Bd2 Rc8 $132 {- with a very good position for Black! For
example} 18. Bd3 Ne7 $5 (18... Nxe5 $5 19. dxe5 Qh4 $132)) (11. dxc5 $2 {
, hoping for 11...Nxc5 12.Bb5+ is strongly met with} O-O $3 $17 12. O-O $2 (12.
c6 Bxc6 13. e5 Nc5 14. Be2 Nfe4 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 $17) (12. cxb6 Nc5 13. Be2 Ncxe4
14. O-O Nxd2 15. Nxd2 axb6 $15) 12... Nxc5 13. Be2 Ncxe4 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 $19) (
11. a3 $2 Bxc3 12. Bxc3 c4 $1 13. Bxc4 Nxe4 $1 $15) 11... Bxd2+ 12. Nxd2 $1 (
12. Qxd2 $2 O-O 13. e5 Bxf3 14. exf6 (14. gxf3 Nd5 15. Be4 cxd4 $1 $15 {
White has too many weaknesses!}) 14... Bc6 15. fxg7 Kxg7 16. O-O-O Qf6 $1 $15 {
is a possible line.}) 12... O-O $3 13. e5 (13. Nd6 Qb8 (13... Bc6 14. e5 Nd5 {
transposes.}) 14. Nxb7 Qxb7 15. e5 Qxg2 16. O-O-O Nd5 17. Bxh7+ Kh8 18. Be4 Qh3
{This is complicated, but it seems that Black is doing well!}) (13. Nf3 $2 c4
$3 14. Qxc4 Nxe4 $17) 13... Nd5 14. Nd6 (14. Bxh7+ Kh8 15. Nd6 Ba6 $5 $132 (
15... Qh4 16. Nxb7 Qxh7 $11)) 14... Bc6 15. Bxh7+ Kh8 16. Be4 {These are all
forced computer moves!} cxd4 $1 17. Qd3 $1 (17. O-O Nxe5 $17) (17. Qxc6 $2 Nxe5
$17) (17. f4 Nc5 $36) 17... Kg8 $1 (17... f5 18. Bxd5 Bxd5 19. Qxd4 Qg5 $132)
18. Qh3 (18. Qxd4 f6 19. Nf3 fxe5 (19... Qe7 $132) 20. Nxe5 Nc5 $1 21. Nxc6
Qxd6 22. Bxd5 exd5 23. Qxd5+ Qxd5 24. Ne7+ Kh7 25. Nxd5 Nd3+ 26. Ke2 Rad8 $1
27. Kxd3 Rxd5+ 28. Ke2 Re5+ 29. Kf1 Rc5 $11) (18. Qg3 f5 $132) (18. Bh7+ Kh8
