e3 b6 {The most natural way to develop.} 9. a3 (9. Bd3 Bb7) 9... Bxc3 10. Bxc3
({After} 10. bxc3 {we can continue with} Bb7 11. Bd3 O-O 12. O-O c5 $11 ({or} 
12... Ne4)) 10... Bb7 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O Ne4 13. Rc1 c5 $11 {Black has an
easy game.} 14. dxc5 Nxc3 15. Rxc3 Nxc5 16. b4 Ne4 17. Rc4 Rc8 18. Qxd8 Rfxd8
19. Rfc1 Rxc4 20. Rxc4 Nd6 21. Rc7 Rc8 22. Rxc8+ Bxc8 23. Kf1 {The endgame is
equal, however, there is still some play in the position.} ({Let me show a
typical idea for Black:} 23. h3 Bb7 24. Kf1 Bxf3 $1 {If Black can execute this
exchange, he gets some practical winning chances.} 25. Bxf3 Nc4 ({If Black
does "nothing", White can never win since Black has a fortress.} 25... e5 {
[%csl Ga5,Gb5,Gc4,Gc5,Gd4,Ge4,Gf4,Gf5]} 26. Ke1 f6 27. Kd2 Kh8 28. Kc3 Kg8 $11)
26. a4 Nb2 27. Bc6 Nd3 28. b5 Kf8 (28... Nc5 {wins a pawn.}) 29. Be4 Nc5 30.
Bc2 h6 $15 {Black can play for a win.}) 23... Bb7 24. Nd2 Kf8 25. f3 Ke7 26.
Bd3 f5 27. f4 g6 28. g3 e5 29. Nc4 exf4 30. Nxd6 Kxd6 31. gxf4 Bd5 32. h4 Bc6
