1. d4 e6 2. c4 Nf6 3. Nc3 {In our repertoire, we will reach the position from
the game via the move order} (3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. Qc2 Bb4 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7.
Qxc3 O-O) 3... Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 O-O 7. Nf3 Nbd7 8. Bf4 $2 (8.
e3 c5 (8... b6 9. Be2 dxc4 10. Qxc4 Bb7 11. O-O c5 $132) 9. dxc5 Ne4 10. Qc2 a5
$3 $132 {[%cal Gd7c5]}) 8... b6 $6 (8... c5 $3 $15 {This is best - see THEORY!
Black gets good counterplay since he is ahead in development. Also White's
queen is misplaced on c3 and can get hit with ...Ne4 or ...Nd5 (after an
exchange on d5).} 9. e3 b6 10. Be2 Ba6 11. b3 Rc8 12. O-O cxd4 13. exd4 dxc4
14. bxc4 Nd5 15. Qc1 Nxf4 16. Qxf4 Bxc4 $19) 9. e3 Ba6 10. Qc2 c5 11. cxd5 Bxf1
12. Kxf1 exd5 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Rd1 Re8 15. h3 Qb6 16. g4 Qb7 17. Kg2 Rac8 18.
Rhe1 h6 19. Re2 Re6 20. Bg3 Ne4 21. Bf4 Rce8 22. Ne1 g5 23. Bh2 d4 24. f3 Nef6
25. e4 Nd5 26. Qd2 N7b6 27. Rc1 Ne3+ 28. Rxe3 dxe3 29. Qe2 Na4 30. Nd3 Qb5 31.
Qxe3 c4 32. Nb4 a5 33. Nd5 Qxd5 0-1

