1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. Bg5 h6 {It is useful to include
this move. We can do so either now, or after 5...Be7 6.e3 and now 6...h6. In
this repertoire I suggest a very interesting and at the same time solid line
for Black. 5...Bb4, transposing to the Ragozin Defence, is also quite good,
but it requires more theoretical knowledge.} 6. Bh4 Be7 7. e3 (7. cxd5 exd5 $1
{transposes to 5.cxd5 ed5 6.Bg5.} (7... Nxd5 $1 8. Bxe7 Qxe7 9. e4 Nxc3 10.
bxc3 O-O 11. Bd3 c5 12. O-O Nf6 $6 (12... b6) 13. Qe2 b6 $2 14. e5 Nd5 15. Qe4
g6 16. c4 Nc7 17. dxc5 Qxc5 18. Rad1 $16)) 7... O-O {This is a very good
position for Black! Solid, but with nice potential for counterplay! Our plan
now is either to play ...c7-c5! or ...dxc4!, followed by ...c7-c5 (or ...a6
first)! Very little concrete theory is needed here!} 8. Rc1 $5 (8. c5 $6 {
This is premature - c4-c5 would have been good for White, if he was better
developed!} Ne4 $1 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Qc2 (10. Nxe4 $2 dxe4 11. Nd2 f5 12. Bc4
Kh8 13. O-O e5 $15) 10... Nxc3 11. Qxc3 c6 12. Bd3 Re8 13. O-O e5 $132) (8. Bd3
dxc4 $1 9. Bxc4 c5 $5 (9... a6 $1 {This is also very good; setting a
positional trap! We are very much threatening ...b7-b5!, with advantage - so
White must play 10.a4! here!} 10. a4 (10. O-O $2 b5 11. Bb3 $6 (11. Bd3 Bb7 (
11... c5 $15) 12. Rc1 c5 $15) (11. Be2 Bb7 12. a4 b4 13. Nb1 c5 14. Nbd2 cxd4 (
14... Rc8 $36) 15. Nxd4 Ne5 $36) 11... c5 $17 12. Qe2 Bb7 13. Rad1 Rc8 $1 $17 (
13... c4 $1 $17) 14. a3 Ne4 15. Bxe7 Nxc3 16. bxc3 Qxe7 $17) 10... c5 11. O-O
cxd4 12. Nxd4 (12. exd4 Nb6 13. Bd3 Nbd5 $132 (13... Bd7 14. Ne5 Bc6 $1 15.
Nxc6 bxc6 16. a5 Nbd5 $132)) 12... Qb6 13. Qe2 Ne5 14. Ba2 Bd7 $15 15. Ne4 Nxe4
16. Bxe7 Rfe8 17. Bh4 Ng6 18. Bg3 Nxg3 19. hxg3 Rac8 $15) 10. O-O (10. dxc5 $6
{This only helps Black.} Nxc5 11. Qxd8 $2 Rxd8 12. O-O b6 $1 $15 {[%cal Gc8b7]
Black has other moves, such as 12...a6 and 12...Bd7 - see Educative Example.})
10... cxd4 11. Nxd4 Qb6 $1 (11... Nb6 $1 12. Be2 Nfd5 $132 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14.
Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bf3 Nf6 16. Rc1 e5 17. Nb5 Rd8 18. Qc2 a6 19. Nc3 Be6 $11) 12.
Qe2 (12. Qb3 g5 13. Bg3 Nh5 14. Qxb6 Nxb6 $15 15. Be2 Nxg3 16. hxg3 Bd7) 12...
Ne5 13. Bb3 Bd7 14. Rfd1 Ng6 (14... Rac8 $132) 15. Bg3 Rac8 $132) (8. Qc2 $5 {
The main move apart from 8.Rc1. However, Black gets a fine game here too!} c5
$1 9. cxd5 (9. O-O-O $2 {As always, castling queenside is bad for White!} cxd4
$17 (9... a6 $15) 10. Nxd4 Nb6 11. cxd5 Nfxd5 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 $17 (
13... exd5 $17)) 9... cxd4 $1 {The most accurate move in this position!} 10.
Nxd4 Nxd5 11. Bxe7 Nxe7 12. Be2 (12. O-O-O $2 a6 (12... Qa5 13. Kb1 Nf6 14. Be2
e5 15. Nb3 Qc7 $15) 13. Kb1 b5 14. Bd3 Bb7 15. Bh7+ Kh8 16. Be4 Qb6 17. Bxb7
Qxb7 18. Qe4 Qb6 $17) (12. Rd1 Qa5 13. Be2 Nf6 14. O-O Bd7 $132) 12... Nf6 13.
O-O Bd7 (13... Qb6 $132) 14. Rfd1 Qa5 $132) (8. a3 $6 c5 $132 9. cxd5 (9. dxc5
dxc4 10. c6 (10. Bxc4 Nxc5) 10... Nb6 11. cxb7 $6 Bxb7 12. Be2 Nbd5 $1 13. Nxd5
Bxd5 14. O-O Rc8 $17 {[%cal Gc4c3,Gd8b6,Gb6a5]}) 9... Nxd5 10. Nxd5 $2 Bxh4 11.
Nxh4 (11. Nc3 cxd4 12. Nxd4 (12. Nxh4 $4 dxc3 $19) 12... Nb6) 11... exd5 $1 (
11... Qxh4 $5 $15) 12. Nf3 c4 13. Be2 b5 14. O-O Nf6 $17) (8. h3 $6 c5 $132) (
8. cxd5 $6 Nxd5 $1 {We always take with the knight on d5 in these lines!} 9.
Bxe7 (9. Bg3 $6 {the bishop is quite irrelevant there !} Nxc3 $1 10. bxc3 c5
$15 11. Bd3 Qa5 12. Rc1 cxd4 13. exd4 b6 14. O-O Bb7 $15 {Black has a very
good version of a position with Hanging Pawns.} 15. Qe2 Rfd8) 9... Qxe7 $1 10.
Nxd5 (10. Be2 $6 Nxc3 11. bxc3 c5 12. O-O b6 13. Qb3 Bb7 $132) (10. Bd3 $6 Nxc3
11. bxc3 c5 12. O-O b6 13. Qe2 Bb7 14. Ba6 (14. e4 Rfc8 $1 $15 15. Rac1 cxd4
16. cxd4 Qa3 $15 (16... Nf6 $15)) 14... Bxa6 15. Qxa6 Nf6 $15) (10. Qc2 $6 Nxc3
11. Qxc3 c5 12. Be2 b6 13. O-O Bb7 {Black is doing great and may soon take
over the initiative as White's bishop is totally useless, while our bishop is
well-placed on b7!}) (10. Rc1 Nxc3 $1 11. Rxc3 c5 12. Bb5 (12. dxc5 $6 Nxc5 13.
Be2 b6 14. O-O Bb7 15. Qc2 a5 $1 $15) 12... cxd4 13. Nxd4 Nf6 $1 (13... Nb6 $1
14. O-O e5 15. Nf3 Bf5 $132) 14. O-O e5 15. Nf3 Bg4 $36) 10... exd5 {Black has
a very good version of the typical Carlsbad structure!} 11. Bd3 Nf6 12. Qc2 (
12. O-O Bg4 $1 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 c6 15. Rac1 a6 (15... Ne8 16. Rfe1 Nd6 $132
) 16. Rfe1 Rfe8 $132) 12... Ne4 13. O-O Bf5 14. Rac1 c6 15. Ne5 Qe6 $132 16. a3
$2 Nd6 17. Bxf5 Nxf5 18. Rfd1 Nd6 $15) 8... c5 $1 (8... dxc4 $5 {Although we
are down one tempo compared to the line with 8.Bd3 dxc4, Black's position is
still very good!} 9. Bxc4 a6 10. a4 $1 (10. O-O $6 b5 11. Bd3 Bb7 $15 12. Qe2
c5 13. Rfd1 cxd4 14. Nxd4 Rc8 $15) 10... c5 $1 {Let's look at some sample
lines to see the typical ideas:} 11. O-O cxd4 12. exd4 (12. Nxd4 Qb6 $1 (12...
Qa5 $1 {Black has a great game - a4 has created some weaknesses!} 13. f4 (13.
Nb3 $2 Qb4) (13. Qe2 $6 Ne5 14. Bb3 Bd7 15. Rfd1 Rac8 $15 16. Bg3 Rfd8 $17 (
16... Nc6 $17 17. Bc2 Rfd8 18. h3 Nxd4 19. Rxd4 Bc6 $17)) (13. Ba2 Qb4 14. Qe2
Nb6 15. f4 Bd7 16. Be1 Qd6 17. Bb3 Nbd5 $132) 13... Qb4 14. Qe2 Nb6 15. Ba2 Bd7
$132) 13. Qb3 (13. Qe2 $2 Ne5 14. Ba2 Bd7 $15 15. Ne4 Rac8 (15... Nxe4) 16.
