1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 O-O 6. e3 Nbd7 7. Bd3 h6 8. Bh4
dxc4 9. Bxc4 a6 {Our move is 9...c5, but 9...a6 is fine.} (9... c5 $1) 10. O-O
(10. a4 $1) 10... b5 {Now, Black gets a good game and is already better.} 11.
Bb3 Bb7 12. Qe2 c5 13. Rfd1 Qb6 $15 14. Rac1 (14. Ne5 Rfd8 15. Nxd7 Rxd7 16.
dxc5 Rxd1+ 17. Rxd1 Qxc5 18. Bc2 g5 $1 19. Bg3 Rd8 ({The computer line is} 
19... b4 $1 20. Na4 Qc6 21. f3 g4 $1 $36) 20. Rxd8+ Bxd8 21. Qd3 Be7 $15) 14...
Rac8 15. a3 cxd4 16. exd4 b4 $1 {I noticed that in many similar positions, the
computer likes this move, exchanging our b-pawn against White's a-pawn.} 17.
axb4 Qxb4 {Black exerts some pressure on White's position and he managed to
win the game.} 18. Ba2 Nb6 19. Ne5 Nfd5 20. Bxd5 Nxd5 21. Nxd5 Bxd5 22. Bxe7
Qxe7 23. Rxc8 Rxc8 24. Qxa6 Rc2 25. Qa3 Qg5 26. g3 Qf5 27. Qe3 Qh3 28. Nf3 Qh5
29. Kg2 Rxb2 30. Rc1 Rb3 31. Rc8+ Kh7 32. Rc3 Qxf3+ 33. Qxf3 Rxc3 34. Qxd5 exd5
35. h4 Rd3 0-1

