1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 Nbd7 8. cxd5
Nxd5 $1 9. Nxd5 Bxh4 10. Nxh4 exd5 $1 {We have seen this idea with the
inclusion of Rc1 and ...c5. Here, the structure is different, though Black
still gets a good game.} 11. Nf3 Nf6 12. h3 ({If} 12. Bd3 {we can play} Bg4 {
- in general we like to get rid of our bishop!} 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 (14. gxf3
$2 c5 $1 15. dxc5 Qa5+ 16. Kf1 Qxc5 $17) 14... c6 15. O-O {Sooner or later, we
transfer our knight to d6 - maybe even now:} Ne8 16. Rfe1 Nd6 17. Qe2 a5 $36 (
17... f5)) 12... Bf5 13. Bd3 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 c6 15. O-O Ne4 16. b4 a6 17. a4 Nd6
$1 $15 {We are very familiar with this strategy! The knight on d6 kills
White's chances for a minority attack. Next, Black will improve his other
pieces and play on the kingside.} 18. Ne5 Re8 19. Rab1 Qh4 20. Qd1 Re6 21. Qg4
Qe7 22. f4 Nc4 23. Qe2 b5 24. axb5 cxb5 25. Rfe1 Re8 26. e4 dxe4 27. Nxc4 bxc4
28. Qxc4 Qd6 29. d5 R6e7 30. Re2 Rc7 31. Qa2 Kh8 32. f5 Re5 33. Rbe1 Rce7 34.
