1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 Nb6 $1 {This is
our first choice: the idea of Nb6 is to play ...Bf5! on the next move! We will
also study 6...c6 as an alternative. Here are some important basic strategic
goals for Black: 1) Exchange pieces and transfer the knight to d6 2) Put the
light-squared bishop on f5 3) Provoke White to play g4 and start counterplay
with ...Ne4 4) Play ...Nh5 and gain the pair of bishops Black must achieve one
of these goals!} 7. Qc2 $5 (7. Nb5 $6 {When playing 6...Nb6, we have to make
sure that we have a good answer to 7.Nb5...} Bb4+ $1 8. Nd2 (8. Bd2 a5 $1 $15 (
8... Bxd2+ $5 9. Nxd2 c6 10. Nc3 Bf5 $15) (8... Be7 $1 $15)) 8... O-O $1 $17 {
This is the key move! The complications are in Black's favour:} 9. a3 (9. Nxc7
$4 Ne4 10. Nxa8 Qf6 $19 11. g3 Bxd2+ 12. Bxd2 Qxf2#) (9. Bxc7 $2 Qd7 10. Bxb6
Qxb5 11. Bc5 Bxc5 12. dxc5 Qxb2 $17) 9... Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 Nc4 11. Qc2 c6 12. Nc3
(12. Nc7 $2 Nh5 13. Bg3 f5 $1 (13... Nxg3 $4 14. hxg3 Qxc7 15. Qxh7#) 14. Nxa8
f4 15. e4 (15. Nc7 fxg3 (15... Qxc7 16. Bh4) 16. hxg3 g6 17. e4 Nd6 18. exd5
Qxc7 $17) 15... fxg3 16. hxg3 Ne3 17. fxe3 Nxg3 $19 18. Rg1 Bg4 $3 19. exd5
cxd5 $19 20. Nc7 Qh4 $19) 12... Nh5 13. Bg3 f5 14. e3 f4 15. Bxf4 Nxf4 16. exf4
Bf5 $19 17. Bd3 Bxd3 18. Qxd3 Nxb2 $19) (7. e3 Bf5 $1 {Black should not miss
his chance to play ...Bf5!} (7... c6 $6 {This is imprecise - however, the
following idea is very instructive!} 8. Bd3 Be7 9. Qc2 (9. h3 $5) 9... Bg4 10.
Ne5 Bh5 11. Rb1 $6 {One weak move like this is enough that Black stands very
well again! This is what we like when playing the QGD!} (11. f3 $1 $16) 11...
Bg6 $1 $132 12. h3 O-O 13. O-O Re8 14. Rfd1 Bd6 15. b4 (15. Nxg6 hxg6 16. Bg5
a5 (16... Be7 17. b4 a6 18. a4 Nh5 19. Bxe7 Qxe7)) 15... Bxd3 16. Nxd3 Nc4 $15)
8. Ne5 (8. Be2 {This doesn't cause any problems.} c6 $5 {With the bishop
already on f5, 8...Bd6 is also good.} (8... Bd6 $5 9. Bxd6 (9. Ne5 O-O (9...
Ne4 $1 10. Nxe4 dxe4 $132) 10. g4 {Black is well-equipped to meet White's
aggression.} (10. Nb5 Bb4+) 10... Be6 11. h4 Ne4 $132 12. Nxe4 $2 dxe4 13. g5
Nd5 14. Bg3 f6 15. gxf6 Qxf6 $17) 9... Qxd6 10. O-O O-O 11. Rc1 c6 12. Ne5 Nbd7
$11 13. f4 $2 Ne4 14. g4 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Be4 $17) 9. O-O Be7 $132 (9... Bd6 $132)
(9... h6 $5 $132) 10. Nh4 Be6 11. Qc2 (11. Nf3 Bg4 $1 12. h3 Bh5 $132) 11...
O-O $132 12. Nf5 ({If White returns with the knight we can either play} 12. Nf3
Nh5 $1 ({or} 12... Bg4 $5 13. h3 Bh5 14. Ne5 Bxe2 15. Qxe2 Re8 16. Rab1 Nfd7 {
We want to exchange the knight on e5 and play ...Nc4.} (16... a5 {is also very
good.}) 17. b4 Nxe5 18. Bxe5 Nc4 19. Bg3 b5 $17)) 12... Bxf5 (12... Bb4 $5 13.
a3 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Bxf5 15. Qxf5 Ne4) 13. Qxf5 Ne8 $132 14. Qc2 Bd6 15. Bg3 $6
Bxg3 16. hxg3 Nd6 $15) (8. Nb5 $2 Bb4+ 9. Nd2 Ne4 $19) (8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 c6
$1 (9... Bd6 $5 10. Bg5 Be7 11. h3 O-O 12. O-O c6 $132) ({Here, we must avoid} 
9... Be7 $2 10. Nb5 $1 $16 Bb4+ 11. Ke2 Bd6 12. Nxd6+ cxd6 13. Bg5 $3 $16) 10.
O-O Be7 11. Rab1 O-O $1 $132 (11... a5 $5 12. h3 O-O $132) 12. h3 a6 13. b4 Bd6
$11) 8... c6 $1 (8... Bd6 $5 {is similar to 8...c6.} 9. Bb5+ $2 c6 10. Nxc6 $2
bxc6 11. Bxc6+ Bd7 $1 12. Bxa8 Bxf4 13. exf4 Qe7+ $5 $17 {Moiseenko-Mista 2018}
) 9. g4 {A double-edged continuation. Black has a sound and solid setup, and
he is well-prepared for such aggression. I AM ALWAYS HAPPY TO SEE SUCH MOVES
BY WHITE!} Be6 $1 $132 {This is the usual response to g4. Black is ready for
counterplay with ...Ne4.} 10. h4 (10. Bg2 $2 Nxg4 $3 {An amazing computer move!
} (10... Nbd7 $1 $36) 11. Nxg4 h5 12. Ne5 g5 13. Bg3 h4 {Black wins back the
piece with a good position.} 14. Nxf7 Bxf7 15. Be5 Rh6 16. e4 Qd7 17. O-O O-O-O
$15) (10. g5 Ne4 $1 $132) (10. f3 $6 Nfd7 $3 $15 {Our knight is restricted by
g4 and f3- so...we move it!} 11. Nxd7 (11. Nd3 h5 $1 $15 12. g5 g6) 11... Qxd7
12. h4 h5 $1 $15) 10... Ne4 $3 11. g5 (11. Bg2 $2 Nxc3 12. bxc3 f6 13. Nd3 Be7
$15) (11. Nxe4 $4 dxe4 $19 12. Qc2 (12. a3 f6) 12... Qd5 $3 13. b3 Qa5+ 14. Kd1
Nd5 15. Bh2 Nc3+ $19) (11. f3 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Be7 13. h5 (13. g5 h6 $15 14. g6 f6
15. Nd3 Nc4) 13... Bh4+ 14. Kd2 Be7 $132) 11... Bb4 $1 $132 (11... Bd6 $1 $132)
) (7. Rc1 $6 {This is too slow.} c6 8. e3 {Black will reach one of his goals.
He can play ...Bf5 right away or play ...Be7, followed by ...Nh5!} Bf5 $1 (8...
Be7 $5 9. Qc2 (9. h3 Bf5 $11) (9. Bd3 Nh5 10. Bg3 g6 $132) 9... Nh5 10. Be5 f6
11. Bg3 O-O 12. Bd3 g6 $1 13. O-O Rf7 $132 (13... Nxg3 14. hxg3 f5 $132)) 9.
Ne5 Bd6 (9... Bb4 $5) (9... Ne4 $5) (9... Be7 $5) 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O Ne4 12.
Nxe4 Bxe4 13. Bd3 Bxd3 14. Nxd3 Bxf4 15. Nxf4 Nc8 16. Rc2 Nd6 $36) (7. h3 $5
Bf5 8. e3 (8. g4 Be4 9. Bg2 c6 (9... Bb4 $5 $132) 10. O-O Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Bd6 $36
) 8... Bd6 $1 (8... h6 $5 9. Ne5 c6 10. Be2 Bd6 $11) 9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. Be2 O-O
11. O-O c6 $132 12. Nh4 Be4 $1 (12... Be6 $1) (12... Bg6 $1)) 7... c6 $1 {
This, and 7...g6, are good moves - Black manages to either play ...Bf5 or to
exchange White's dark-squared bishop with ...Nh5.} (7... g6 $5 {is another
playable and good option!} 8. e3 Bf5 9. Bd3 (9. Qb3 Nh5 $1 10. Bg5 f6 11. Bh4
g5 12. Bg3 c6 $15 (12... Nxg3 13. hxg3 c6 $15)) 9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 c6 11. O-O
Be7 $5 (11... Bg7 $6 {The bishop is misplaced on g7.} 12. b4 O-O 13. b5 $14 {
1/2-1/2 (20) Kasparov,G-Eingorn,V/Moscow 1988/URS-ch}) 12. h3 (12. Bh6 {
does not bother us. We can play either} Ng4 ({or} 12... Bf8 13. Bxf8 Kxf8 $11)
13. Bf4 O-O 14. h3 Nf6 $13) 12... O-O 13. Bg5 (13. Rac1 Re8) (13. Rab1 a5 $1) (
13. a3 a5 $1) 13... Nbd7 14. Rab1 a5 15. a3 Re8 16. Bxf6 (16. Rfd1 Ne4) 16...
Nxf6 17. Rfc1 (17. b4 b5 $1 $15) 17... Bd6 18. b4 {We are already quite
familiar with the typical ideas:} Qe7 $1 $15 (18... b5 $5)) 8. e3 (8. h3 {
White defends against ...Nh5, but now we are in time with} g6 $1 {, followed
by ...Bf5.} (8... Be7 $6 {is too slow.} 9. e3 g6 $2 10. Bd3 $14 {Black
achieves none of the basic goals.}) 9. e3 Bf5 10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 Bd6 $1 (
11... a5 $5 12. O-O Bg7 13. Ne5 O-O $11 {Since White has lost some time with 8.
h3, even a setup with ...Bg7 works for Black. For example} 14. Qc2 Nfd7 15. Nd3
Re8 16. Rac1 Nf8 (16... Bf8 $5) 17. Rfd1 Ne6 18. Bg3 Qe7 $132) 12. Bh6 {
can simply be met with} Bf8 13. Bf4 (13. Bxf8 Kxf8 14. O-O Kg7) 13... Bd6 $11 (
{If Black does not want to repeat the moves we can play on with} 13... Bg7))
8... Nh5 $1 {This is the best move!} (8... Bd6 $6 {This is objectively dubious,
but the following game is very instructive!} 9. Bg5 Be7 10. Bd3 Nh5 11. Bxe7
Qxe7 12. O-O-O $6 {The computer almost never likes 0-0-0 for White in such
positions!} Bg4 13. Be2 O-O 14. h3 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Nf6 16. g4 Rfe8 17. Rhe1 Ne4
$1 18. Bg2 Rac8 $15 (18... Nxc3 $3 {(Stockfish)} 19. Qxc3 Qh4 $3 20. Re2 Re6 $3
21. Kb1 Rae8 $17 (21... h5 $17) 22. b3 Nc8 23. Rdd2 Nd6 24. Qd3 h5 25. gxh5
Qxh5) 19. Kb1 Nxc3+ 20. Qxc3 Qf6 $15) (8... Be7 $2 {This is a very instructive
mistake—check the comments below! SUPER SOS! Black should not develop his
pieces without thinking.} 9. h3 $1 $16 {After 9.h3! Black fails to achieve any
of the basic goals!} g6 10. Bd3) 9. Be5 (9. Bg5 f6 $1 {The most ambitious
continuation. 9...Be7 is a solid alternative.} (9... Be7 $5 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11.
Be2 (11. Bd3 Nf4) 11... g6 12. O-O O-O 13. Ne5 Ng7 $132 {Black's bishop will
come to f5.}) 10. Bh4 g5 $1 (10... g6 $5) 11. Bg3 Be6 $1 $36 {Black will
capture on g3 at some point and is doing great. For example} (11... Bg4 $1 12.
Bd3 Qd7 $1 $36 13. O-O-O ({After} 13. O-O {Black can start an attack with} Nxg3
14. hxg3 h5 $132) 13... Nxg3 14. hxg3 h5 $13)) (9. Bd3 Nxf4 10. exf4 Bd6 11.
Ne2 g6 $1 (11... Qf6 $1 12. Ne5 g6 13. h4 Be6 $132 14. Kf1 O-O-O 15. a4 Nc4 $3
$15) 12. h4 Be6 13. h5 Qf6 14. g3 O-O-O $132) 9... f6 10. Bg3 Be6 $1 (10... g6
$1 11. Bd3 Be7 12. O-O Nxg3 $5 (12... O-O $132 {is also possible - the
sacrifice on g6 does not work.}) 13. hxg3 f5 14. Ne5 Bd6 15. f4 O-O $132) 11.
Bd3 g6 12. Bh4 $6 (12. O-O Nxg3 13. hxg3 f5 14. Ne5 Bd6 15. f4 O-O $132) 12...
g5 13. Bg3 Qd7 14. O-O Nxg3 (14... O-O-O $132) (14... Be7 $5 $132) 15. hxg3 h5
