{This game (and the analysis) is very important for the understanding of the
Carlsbad structure! If the light-squared bishops have been exchanged, Black
has a perfect game. In this he can exchange the dark-squared bishops as well
and play a Nd6 strategy. However, if the light-squared bishops are exchanged,
and White manages to exchange his remaining bishop for a knight, we should
play ...a5 to stop b4!, and relocate the bishop to d6! The knight can stay on
b6 or f6.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 Nb6 7.
e3 Bf5 8. Bd3 (8. Nb5 Bb4+ 9. Nd2 O-O) 8... Bxd3 9. Qxd3 c6 10. O-O Be7 {
In general, these positions with only the light square bishops have been
exchanged tend to be very good for Black! Due to the potential weakness of c4,
it is not easy for White to go for a minority attack.} 11. Rab1 (11. Bg5 a5 $5)
(11. h3 O-O 12. Bg5 Ne4 $1 (12... a5 $5 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. a3 Be7 $1 15. Qc2 Re8
16. Rab1 Bd6 $15 (16... Nc4 $15))) 11... a5 $1 (11... O-O $5 12. b4 a6 13. a4
Re8 $132 {We already know Black's setup with the knight on b6 and pawns on a6
and c6.} 14. b5 $2 cxb5 15. axb5 a5 $1 $15) 12. Be5 Nbd7 13. Rfc1 O-O 14. Qc2 (
14. Bxf6 Nxf6 15. Qc2 Bd6 16. a3 Qe7 $15 (16... Re8 17. b4 Qe7 $15 {Just like
in the game Megaranto-Ding Liren!})) 14... Re8 15. a3 Nb6 (15... Nxe5 $3 $15 {
Black missed his chance to get an advantage !} {Probably, Black was afraid of}
16. dxe5 ({Black's position is perfect after} 16. Nxe5 Bd6 17. Nf3 (17. f4 $2
Rc8 18. Qf2 Rc7 $1 $17 {[%csl Ge4]} (18... Nd7 $1 $17) (18... b5 $5 $17)) 17...
Qe7 $15 (17... h5 $1) 18. h3 g6 19. Re1 Kg7 $15) 16... Nd7 17. e4 d4 $3 {
This is an important resource.} 18. Nxd4 (18. e6 dxc3 19. exd7 Qxd7 20. Qxc3
Red8 $1 $15) 18... Nxe5 19. Rd1 Qb6 20. Nf5 Bf8 $17) 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Na4 Nc4
18. Nd2 Nd6 $36 19. Nc5 g6 20. a4 Qc8 21. b4 axb4 22. Rxb4 Bd8 23. Rb3 Ra7 $15
24. Rcb1 Ba5 25. Nf3 Kg7 26. g3 Re7 27. Ne5 f6 28. Nf3 Nc4 29. Qd1 Nd6 30. Qc2
Nc4 31. Qd1 Nd6 1/2-1/2

