1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bf4 c6 $5 {This is an
interesting alternative to 6...Nb6. BE CAREFUL! After 6...c6, we won't just
continue with regular Carlsbad development like ...Be7 and ...0-0 - we have
concrete ideas in mind! We go for either 6...c6 7.e3 Nh5!, 6...c6 7.h3 Ne4!,
or 6...c6 7.Qc2 Nb6!} 7. h3 (7. Qc2 Bb4 $5 {This is another interesting and
extremely rare alternative to 7...Nb6!} (7... Nb6 $1 {transposes to 6.Bf4 Nb6
7.Qc2 c6.}) 8. a3 $1 (8. e3 Nh5 9. Bg5 Ndf6 $3 10. Bd3 (10. h3 h6) 10... h6 11.
Bh4 Bd6 (11... g5 $2 12. Bg3 Nxg3 13. hxg3 {and the annoying threat of Nxg5 is
forcing us to play an undesirable move!} Ng4 (13... g4 14. Ne5 $16) 14. O-O $16
) 12. O-O-O Be6 13. Rhe1 $6 (13. h3 g5) 13... g5 14. Bg3 Nxg3 15. hxg3 Qc7 16.
Kb1 O-O-O $36) 8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 (9. Qxc3 $6 Ne4 10. Qc2 Nf8 $36 11. e3 Ng6
12. Bd3 Bf5) 9... Ne4 10. Nd2 Nxd2 11. Qxd2 $14) (7. e3 Nh5 $1 8. Bg5 (8. Bd3
$6 Nxf4 9. exf4 Bd6 10. Qd2 O-O 11. O-O Re8 12. g3 (12. Ne5 Nf8 $15) 12... Nf8
13. Rfe1 Rxe1+ 14. Rxe1 Bh3 15. Ng5 Bg4 $132) 8... Be7 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 {This
leads to typical Carlsbad play - no concrete theory is needed at all! Here are
some sample lines:} 10. Be2 (10. Bd3 $6 Nf4 11. O-O Nxd3 12. Qxd3 O-O 13. Rab1
Nb6 $36) (10. Qc2 Nb6 $5 (10... O-O $5 11. Bd3 g6 12. O-O Ndf6 13. Rab1 Ng7 14.
b4 a6 15. a4 Bg4 16. Ne5 Bf5 $132) 11. Be2 (11. O-O-O $6 Nf6 12. Bd3 Bg4 13.
Kb1 O-O-O 14. Ka1 Kb8 15. Rc1 Rhe8 16. h3 Bc8 17. Ne5 g6 $11) 11... Bg4 12. h3
Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Nf6 14. O-O O-O $132) 10... g6 (10... Nhf6) 11. O-O O-O 12. Qc2
Nb6 $5 $132 (12... Ndf6 $5 13. Ne5 Ng7 14. Qb3 Nf5 $11) (12... Ng7 $5 13. a3
Nb6 14. b4 a6 15. Nd2 Nf5 $132) 13. Ne5 (13. Bd3 Ng7) 13... Ng7 14. b3 Bf5 15.
Qb2 Nd7 $132) 7... Ne4 $1 {This is the best move, with nice counterplay for
Black!} 8. Nxe4 (8. Rc1 $6 Bd6 $1 9. Bxd6 Nxd6 10. e3 Nb6 11. Bd3 Bf5 $132) (8.
e3 $6 Bb4 $1 (8... Bd6 $5 9. Bxd6 Nxd6 10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O Nb6 12. Qc2 g6 $132)
9. Rc1 Qa5 10. Qb3 c5 $1 11. a3 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 O-O $132) 8... dxe4 9. Nd2 f5 $1
{This is an interesting and extremely rare move. It leads to the original
unclear play! Remember to put the knight on b6 (not on f6) because we want to
control the c4 square before eventually going to d5!} (9... Nf6 $1 {This is
simple and very good!} 10. e3 Nd5 11. Be5 f6 12. Bg3 f5 13. Rc1 Be6 $11 (13...
Be7 $5) (13... Bd6 $5)) (9... g5 $6 {Unfortunately this doesnt work!} 10. Bg3 (
10. Bh2 $6 e3 $5 11. fxe3 Nb6 12. Qc2 Bb4 $13) 10... e3 11. fxe3 Nb6 12. Rc1
$16 (12. a3 $5)) 10. e3 Nb6 11. Be2 (11. Nc4 $2 Bb4+) (11. Qb3 a5 12. a3 (12.
a4 Bb4) 12... a4 13. Qc2 (13. Qa2 $6 Nd5 14. Be5 Bd6 $17) 13... Be7 $11) 11...
Be7 (11... Bd6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. O-O Be6 $11) 12. O-O Be6 13. Nb3 (13. a3 O-O
14. Qc2 a5 15. Nc4 Nd5 16. Bh2 a4 17. Ne5 Bd6 18. Rac1 Kh8 19. Bc4 Qe7 20. Kh1
Bg8 $132) 13... Nd5 14. Be5 O-O $11 *

