1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. cxd5 ({After} 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 Be7
{and only now} 7. cxd5 {, my recommendation was} Nxd5 $1 {However, 7...exd5!
is also good, transposing to the main line of this lesson.} (7... exd5 $1 8. e3
c6 9. Qc2 (9. Bd3 Ne4) 9... Nh5)) 5... exd5 6. Bg5 c6 7. e3 h6 8. Bh4 Be7 $1 {
A sound and solid line! Remember : once again our plan is NOT to continue with
regular Carlsbad moves like ...Be7-0-0-Re8-Nf8 etc, but to play some concrete
moves! After 8...Be7 9.Bd3 we play 9...Ne4! and after 8...Be7 9.Qc2 we gor for
9...Nh5!} 9. Bd3 {This is what most players will go for but 9.Qc2!? must be a
bit better!} (9. Qc2 $5 Nh5 $1 (9... Ne4 $2 {Here, 9...Ne4 DOES NOT WORK!} 10.
Nxe4 dxe4 (10... Bxh4 11. Nd6+ $16) 11. Qxe4 $18) 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Be2 $1 {
This may be White's best continuation, leading to typical Carlsbad play!} (11.
O-O-O {If White castles queenside in this line, we also castle to the
queenside!} Nb6 $1 12. Bd3 Nf6 13. Kb1 (13. Ne5 Ng4 $1 14. Nxg4 Bxg4 15. Rde1
O-O-O 16. f3 Be6 17. Kb1 Kb8 18. a3 h5 19. h4 g6 $132) 13... Be6 (13... Bg4 $5)
14. Rc1 Nfd7 $1 $11 15. Ka1 O-O-O 16. Na4 Nxa4 17. Qxa4 {White wants to attack
with Rc3 etc. but we are in time to defend.} Kb8 18. Rc3 Nb6 19. Qa5 Nc4 $132)
(11. Bd3 $6 {runs into} Nf4 12. Bf1 O-O (12... Nh5 $11)) (11. h3 g6 (11... O-O
$2 12. g4 $40) 12. Be2 Ng7 13. O-O Nf6 $132) 11... Nhf6 12. O-O O-O 13. a3 Re8
(13... Nb6 14. h3 (14. b4 Bg4 $1) 14... Ne4 $132) 14. b4 Nb6 $1 15. Rab1 Bg4
$132) (9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Ne4 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Qc2 (12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Nd2 Nb6
14. Qc2 f5 15. a3 Be6 16. Nc4 Nxc4 17. Bxc4 Rad8 18. Bxe6+ Qxe6 19. b4 f4 $15 (
19... g5 $5)) 12... Ndf6 13. Ne5 Bf5 $132) 9... Ne4 $1 10. Bxe7 (10. Bxe4 $6
dxe4 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Nd2 Nf6 {I prefer this over 12...f5. Black will
continue with ...0-0, ...Bf5, with a good game. The e4-pawn gives Black a
space advantage on the kingside, with potential attacking chances.} 13. Qc2 (
13. O-O O-O 14. Qc2 Bf5 15. f4 $6 Rac8 $3 (15... exf3 $4 16. Qxf5 Qxe3+ 17. Rf2
$18) 16. h3 Nd5 $36) 13... Bf5 14. f3 $4 exf3 15. Qxf5 Qxe3+ 16. Kd1 fxg2 17.
Kc2 gxh1=Q 18. Rxh1 O-O {0-1 Petrovic,A-Volkov,M/chess.com INT 2022}) (10. Nxe4
$4 dxe4 $19) (10. Bg3 $6 Nxg3 11. hxg3 O-O {White will never be ably to attack
via the h-file since he will not manage to play g4-g5.} 12. Qc2 Nf6 13. O-O Re8
14. Rab1 Bd6 $15) 10... Qxe7 11. Qc2 $1 (11. Rc1 Ndf6 12. O-O Bf5 $1 $132 {
A recurring theme - taking control of the b1-h7 diagonal is important.} (12...
Nd6 $6 {gives White the chance to play.} 13. Qc2) (12... Bg4 $1 $132)) (11. O-O
$5 Ndf6 $1 (11... O-O $1 12. Qc2 Ndf6) 12. Qc2 O-O {transposes.}) (11. Bxe4
dxe4 12. Nd2 Nf6 13. Qc2 Bf5 $11 {transposes to 10.Bxe4.}) 11... Ndf6 12. O-O (
12. Ne5 $1 {SUPER SOS! Don't fall for the trick with Nxc6!} O-O $1 (12... Bf5
$4 13. Nxc6 $1 bxc6 14. Nxe4 Qb4+ 15. Nd2 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Qxb2 17. O-O $18) 13.
O-O Bf5 $1 $132) (12. O-O-O $2 {is again dubious. For example} Bf5 $15 ({or} 
12... O-O 13. Kb1 Bf5 $15) 13. Ne5 O-O 14. Kb1 Nxc3+ 15. Qxc3 Bxd3+ 16. Nxd3
Rfe8 $15) 12... O-O {Now, our plan is to play ...Bf5!, followed by exchanging
some pieces! Here are some sample lines:} 13. Nd2 (13. Ne5 Bf5 $132 {Next, we
want to exchange on c3, when White can play bxc3!?. For example} 14. a4 (14. a3
Nxc3 15. bxc3 (15. Qxc3 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Ne4 $15 (16... c5)) 15... Bxd3 16. Nxd3
Ne4 17. a4 Nd6 $132) (14. Rae1 $6 Nxc3 15. bxc3 (15. Qxc3 Bxd3 16. Nxd3 Ne4
$132) 15... Bxd3 16. Nxd3 (16. Qxd3 c5 17. c4 cxd4 18. exd4 dxc4 19. Qxc4 Qd6
$15) 16... Rac8 $5 (16... Ne4 17. c4 dxc4 18. Ne5 (18. Qxc4 Nd2) 18... Nd6 19.
Nxc4 Nxc4 20. Qxc4 Rfd8 $132 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gb7b6,Gc6c5]}) (16... b5 $5 17. f3
Rae8 18. Nc5 (18. Ne5 Qc7) 18... Nd7 19. Nxd7 Qxd7 $15) 17. c4 dxc4 (17... Rfe8
$2 18. c5) 18. Qxc4 Ne4 $132) (14. Ne2 {White threatens f3.} Bh7 $1 15. f3 (15.
Ng3 $2 Nxg3 16. hxg3 Bxd3 17. Nxd3 Ne4 $17) 15... Nd6 16. Bxh7+ Nxh7 $11 {
Let me construct a position without knights:} 17. Nf4 Nf6 18. Nfd3 Nd7 19. Nxd7
Qxd7 20. Nc5 Qe7 21. Rab1 Ne4 22. Nxe4 Qxe4 23. Qd2 Qe7 24. Rbc1 Rfe8 25. Rfe1
Rad8 {White would be fine with his pawn on f2 instead of f3!} {If} 26. e4 dxe4
27. fxe4 {The hanging pawns in the centre are more of a liability than a
strength.} Qh4 $15 {[%csl Rd4,Re4]} (27... Rd6 $5)) 14... Bh7 (14... Nxc3 15.
Bxf5 Nce4 16. f3 (16. a5 a6 17. Rae1 Nd6 $15) 16... Nd6 17. Bd3 Nd7 $1 $36 18.
Nxd7 (18. f4 Nf6) 18... Qxd7 19. Rfe1 f5 $36) 15. a5 a6 16. Rfe1 Nd6 $36) (13.
Rac1 Bf5 14. Bxe4 (14. a3 Nxc3 15. Bxf5 Nce4 (15... Nb5 16. Ne5 Nd6 17. Bd3 Nd7
18. f4 Nf6 $1 $132)) 14... Bxe4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Nd2 Nd6 $1 {We have reached
the perfect position.} 17. g3 $2 {and 17.h3 are the worst positional moves for
White here since they create targets on the kingside!}) (13. Rab1 Bf5 14. b4 $2
{White's minority attack is ineffective in this situation.} Nxc3 (14... a5 $1
$15 15. b5 $2 Rfc8 $3 $17 16. b6 c5) 15. Qxc3 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 a6 17. a4 Ne4 $15
18. b5 $2 cxb5 $1 (18... axb5 $5 19. axb5 Ra3 $17) 19. axb5 a5 $17) 13... Re8
$5 (13... Bf5 $5 {is also simple and good of course.} 14. Rab1 $6 (14. Bxe4
dxe4 $132) 14... Nxd2 15. Qxd2 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 a6 $1 17. b4 b5 18. a4 Ne8 19. e4
$2 dxe4 20. Qxe4 Qd7 21. axb5 axb5 22. Rfd1 Nf6 $17) 14. Rae1 Bf5 15. Ndxe4
dxe4 16. Bc4 Rad8 $5 $132 {Black has extra space due to his e4 pawn and
chances to play against the white king!} 17. a3 Rd6 18. b4 Qd7 $36 (18... h5 $5
$36) *

