1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 c6 7. e3 h6 8. Bh4
Be7 9. Bd3 (9. Be2 Ne4 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. O-O (11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Nd2 Nf6 13. O-O
O-O $132) 11... Ndf6 12. Ne5 Bf5 $11) 9... Ne4 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Qc2 Ndf6 12.
O-O O-O 13. Ne5 Bf5 14. a4 {The computer approves of this move.} Bh7 15. a5 a6
16. Ra3 Rfe8 (16... Nxc3 $1 {was also good since White cannot play bxc3 due to
the rook on a3!}) 17. Nxe4 Nxe4 (17... Bxe4 $1 18. Bxe4 Nxe4 19. Rd3 Nd6 {
Due to White's pawn on a5, he can no longer go for a minority attack while
Black can play on the kingside. For example} 20. b4 f6 21. Ng6 Qf7 22. Nf4 Re7
$15 {Black is better. Let me bring about a position without the knights:} 23.
Rdd1 Nc4 24. Nd3 Rae8 25. Nb2 Nxb2 26. Qxb2 f5 $15 {If White's pawn was still
on a4, the position would be equal or better for White since in that case, he
could play b4-b5!}) 18. Rc1 Rad8 19. Rb3 f6 20. Nf3 g5 21. Bxe4 Bxe4 22. Qe2
Qf7 23. Rb6 Re7 24. Nd2 Bf5 25. Nb3 Rde8 26. Nc5 Bc8 27. Qf3 {White misses a
great chance!} (27. b4 $3 {was extremely strong since Black is powerless
against b4-b5!} h5 28. b5 $3 cxb5 29. Qf3 Rf8 30. Rd6 $16) 27... Kg7 28. Qg3
Kh7 29. Nd3 Rg8 30. Qd6 Rd7 31. Qg3 Re7 32. Qd6 h5 33. Nc5 h4 {Since White
missed his chance, Black slowly but surely starts creating threats on the
kingside.} 34. h3 Rg7 35. Kh2 Qg6 36. Rb3 g4 37. hxg4 Bxg4 38. Nd3 Rd7 39. Qb8
h3 40. Nf4 Qe4 41. Qf8 hxg2 42. Qxf6 Kg8 43. Kg1 Qh7 44. Nxg2 Bh3 45. Kf1 Rdf7
46. Qe5 Rxg2 47. Ke1 Rg1+ 0-1

