1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 h6 7. Bh4 Bb4 $1 {
We will also examine this more aggressive and more risky setup!} 8. e3 (8. a3 {
is rather slow.} Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 c5 10. e3 Qa5 $36) (8. Bxf6 Qxf6 (8... Nxf6 $4
9. Qa4+) 9. a3 (9. Qb3 Qd6 $1 10. a3 Ba5 11. e3 c6 $132) 9... Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 c5
$36 11. e3 c4 $1) (8. Nd2 $5 c6 (8... Nb6 $5 9. e3 Bf5 $5 10. Qf3 Bg6 11. Bxf6
Qxf6 12. Qxf6 gxf6 13. a3 Be7 $132) 9. e3 O-O 10. Bd3 Re8 11. O-O Nf8 12. Qc2 (
12. a3 Bd6 $132) 12... Bd6 13. Bg3 Bxg3 14. hxg3 Bg4 $5 $132) (8. Rc1 c6 9. e3
g5 10. Bg3 Ne4 $132) 8... g5 $1 9. Bg3 Ne4 10. Nd2 $5 {This is the main line!
10.Nd2 offers a pawn sacrifice, but we are not accepting it!} (10. Qb3 $5 {
another interesting move!} c5 $1 {This is by far the best move!} 11. dxc5 (11.
Rc1 $5 Qa5 $1 12. Nd2 (12. a3 $2 Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 c4 $1 14. Qb2 (14. Qc2 Qxa3 $5
$17 {Simple and good !} 15. Nd2 Nxg3 16. hxg3 Kf8 $17 (16... b5 $17)) (14. Qb4
Qxb4 $1 15. axb4 a5 $17) 14... Nb6 $1 15. Bc7 Kd7 $3 16. Bxb6 axb6 $1 $17 (
16... Qxb6 $5) 17. Ne5+ Ke7 18. f3 Nd6 $17 19. h4 Be6) 12... Nxd2 13. Kxd2 c4
14. Qc2 O-O $5 (14... Nf6) (14... Qxa2 $5 $132) 15. a3 Bxc3+ 16. Qxc3 Qd8 $132
17. h4 $2 Nf6 18. f3 g4 19. Be5 Re8 $36 20. Be2 b5 21. Ke1 a5) (11. Nd2 Nxd2
12. Kxd2 O-O $1 13. Qxd5 cxd4 (13... Nf6 $5 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15. Bd3 cxd4 16. exd4
Rxd4 $11 17. Be5 $2 Ne4+ 18. Kc2 Rxd3 19. Nxe4 Rd8 $17 20. Nf6+ Kf8 21. Kb3 a5
$19) 14. Qxd4 Nc5 $1 $36) (11. a3 $2 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 c4 13. Qb2 Qb6 $1 14. Qc2
Ndf6 $17 (14... Qa5 $15) 15. Be5 (15. Ne5 Bf5) 15... Bf5 $17 (15... O-O $17))
11... Bxc3+ $1 12. bxc3 Ndxc5 13. Qa3 (13. Bb5+ $5 {This leads to a forced
draw !} Bd7 (13... Kf8 $6 14. Qb4 $16) 14. Qxd5 $1 Bxb5 15. Qe5+ Kd7 16. Qf5+ (
16. O-O-O+ Bd3 17. Ne1 Kc6 18. Nxd3 Nxd3+ 19. Rxd3 Qxd3 20. Qc7+ Kb5 21. Qxb7+
Kc5 22. Qc7+ Kb5 23. Qb7+ Kc5 24. Qc7+ $11) 16... Ke7 {(or ...Ke7)} 17. Qe5+
$11 Kd7 18. Qf5+ $11) 13... O-O $1 $132 14. Be2 Re8 $1 $13 (14... Bg4 $5) 15.
O-O (15. Rd1 Qe7 16. c4 (16. Rxd5 Nd3+) 16... dxc4 17. Bxc4 Be6 18. Bxe6 Nxe6
$132) 15... h5 $132 16. h4 Nxg3 17. fxg3 Ne4 $132) (10. Qc2 $5 {This takes us
by force into a very complicated position that is at last equal for Black! (
the same line is also presented in the move order 4...Nbd7 5.Qc2!? Bb4 6.cxd5
exd5 7.Bg5 h6 8.Bh4 g5 9.Bg3 Ne4 10.e3 h5! etc.} h5 $1 11. Bd3 h4 $3 12. Bxe4
dxe4 13. Qxe4+ Kf8 14. Be5 f6 15. Nxg5 Nxe5 $1 16. dxe5 Bxc3+ 17. bxc3 fxg5 18.
O-O Kg7 $1 19. f4 Bd7 $3 20. f5 (20. Qxb7 Rf8 21. Rad1 Qc8 22. Qd5 Bg4 23. e6 (
23. Rd4 Qe6 $17) 23... Qxe6 24. Qxg5+ Qg6 $17) 20... Bc6 $3 21. Qg4 Kh6 $1 22.
Rad1 Qe7 23. e6 Qf6 $1 $17) (10. Rc1 $2 {This is a well-known mistake - for
concrete reasons: we go after White's bishop!} h5 $1 11. h3 (11. Qb3 Bxc3+ 12.
bxc3 c6 {We support d5, renewing the threat of ...h4.} 13. h4 Nxg3 14. fxg3 g4
15. Ng5 Qc7 16. Kf2 Rh6 $17) 11... Nxg3 12. fxg3 Qe7 13. Kf2 Nf6 $17) 10...
Nxg3 $1 11. hxg3 c6 $1 {Black has two good plans: A) ...c6!-Kf8!-Nf6-Kg7!, and
after a3 we go ...Ba5! with great play. B) ...Nb6!, followed by ...Be6 -c6
-Qe7 or ...Qf6 and 0-0-0. After a3 we can go ...Bd6, ...Be7, or for my
favourite move ...Bf8! (intending ...Bg7!) HERE ARE SOME SAMPLE LINES!
Concrete theory is not needed from now and on - just plans and ideas!} (11...
Nb6 $1 12. Bd3 (12. a3 Bf8 $5 (12... Be7 $5) (12... Bd6 $5 13. Qc2 c6 $132) 13.
Qc2 c6 14. Bd3 (14. O-O-O $6 Be6 15. Bd3 Bg7 (15... Qf6 16. f4 O-O-O $132) 16.
Kb1 Qe7 17. Bf5 O-O-O 18. Nb3 Bxf5 19. Qxf5+ Kb8 $132) 14... Be6 15. b4 (15.
O-O Qf6 $132 (15... g4 $132)) 15... h5 16. Nb3 Qf6 17. Nc5 O-O-O $1 $36 (17...
Bc8 $1 $132)) (12. Qc2 c6 13. a3 Bf8 (13... Bd6) 14. Be2 Be6 15. O-O h5 $132 (
15... Bg7 $132)) 12... Be6 13. a3 Bd6 (13... Bf8 14. Qc2 c6 (14... Bg7 $6 15.
Nb3 $16) 15. b4 h5 $132) 14. Qc2 c6 $132) 12. a3 (12. Qc2 Kf8 $1 (12... Nf6 $6
{SUPER SOS! Everyone is committing this mistake, mixing up the move order! Now,
White can play Nf3, forcing us to put the well placed ...Nf6 on a worse
square! That's why we should play ...Kf8! first, and only afterwards ...Nf6!
in order to be able to defend against Nxg5 with ...Kg7!} 13. Nf3 $1 Ne4 (13...
Ng4 14. a3 Be7 15. Bd3 $14) 14. Bd3 Bf5 15. g4 $16) 13. a3 Ba5 $1 14. Bd3 Nf6
15. b4 (15. Nb3 Bc7 16. O-O-O Kg7 {Black is at least equal!}) (15. Nf3 Kg7 $1
$15) 15... Bc7 16. O-O (16. Bf5 $6 Kg7 17. Bxc8 Qxc8 $15 (17... Rxc8 18. Nb3
Bd6 19. Nc5 Qe7 $15)) 16... Kg7 $1 $36 (16... h5 $1 $36)) (12. Bd3 Kf8 13. Qc2
Nf6 14. a3 Ba5 $132) 12... Ba5 $1 {This is our main idea after ...c6.} (12...
Bf8 $5) (12... Be7 $5) 13. Bd3 (13. b4 Bc7 14. Bd3 Kf8 $1 15. b5 Nf6 16. bxc6
bxc6 17. Qc2 Kg7 $132 {It is not easy for White to castle kingside because we
are ready for a fast ...h5-h4 attack!}) 13... Kf8 14. Qc2 Nf6 15. O-O-O Kg7 16.
Kb1 Re8 $1 (16... Be6 $6 17. Nb3 Bb6 18. f3 $1 (18. f4 $6 Bg4 19. Rde1 {
1-0 (43) Nakamura,H-Anand,V/London 2016/CBM 176} Qd7 $1 $15 {[%cal Ga8e8]})
18... Qd6 19. g4 $14) 17. Nb3 Bxc3 $1 (17... Bc7 $1 $132) 18. Qxc3 Ng4 19. Qc2
Qf6 20. Rhf1 b6 21. Rc1 Bd7 $15 {We can continue with ...a5; White will never
get f3 in!} *

