1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 {Again, we will transpose to our repertoire,
starting from a totally different move order.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Bg5
h6 7. Bh4 Nbd7 8. e3 g5 9. Bg3 Ne4 10. Nd2 Nxg3 11. hxg3 c6 12. Bd3 Nf6 $6 ({
As we know from discussing the theory,} 12... Nb6 {is the other possible plan.
For example} 13. a3 Bf8 14. Qc2 Be6 15. O-O-O Qf6 16. Nf3 O-O-O 17. Kb1 Kb8 18.
Rc1 Bd6 19. e4 dxe4 20. Nxe4 Qe7 21. Nxd6 Qxd6 $15) (12... Kf8 $1) 13. Qc2 (13.
Nf3 $1) 13... Be6 (13... Kf8 $1) 14. Nf3 $1 {Due to the threat of Nxg5, Black
is forced to play} Ng4 15. Bf5 $2 {This almost never poses problems.} (15. a3
Bd6 16. e4 $14) 15... Bxf5 16. Qxf5 Qd7 17. Qxd7+ Kxd7 {Black is very
comfortable in this endgame.} 18. Nh2 Nf6 19. Ke2 a5 ({Black could have
secured an advantage with} 19... Bxc3 20. bxc3 Ne4 21. Rac1 b5 22. Nf3 h5 $17
23. Ne5+ Kc7 $1 24. Nxf7 $2 Rhf8 $19) 20. Nf3 1/2-1/2

